NOTES_LUKE = {
    1: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Epeidēper" (ἐπειδήπερ) is a hapax legomenon in the NT, an intensified form of "epeidē" meaning "inasmuch as indeed." It signals Luke\'s elevated literary register. "Peplērophorēmenōn" (πεπληροφορημένων, from plērophoreō, Strong\'s G4135) means "fully accomplished" or "fully established," indicating certainty and divine completion of the events narrated.',
        2: 'GREEK: "Autoptai" (αὐτόπται, Strong\'s G845) is a hapax legomenon in the NT, literally "self-seers" or "eyewitnesses." It is the origin of the English "autopsy." "Hypēretai tou logou" — "servants of the Word" — indicates a recognized class of authoritative tradents in the early community. THEOLOGICAL: Luke distinguishes himself from the eyewitnesses, establishing a second-generation perspective while affirming the apostolic chain of testimony.',
        3: 'GREEK: "Anōthen" (ἄνωθεν, Strong\'s G509) can mean "from above" (divine perspective, cf. John 3:3) or "from the beginning." Luke likely intends both senses — tracing events from their origin with divinely guided accuracy. "Kratiste" (κράτιστε) is a title of social rank ("most excellent"), used also for Roman governors Felix (Acts 23:26) and Festus (Acts 26:25). HISTORICAL: This formal dedication follows Greco-Roman literary convention for historical works, placing Luke\'s Gospel in the genre of orderly historical narrative.',
        5: 'HISTORICAL: Herod the Great reigned 37–4 BC. The priestly division of Abijah was the eighth of twenty-four courses established by David (1 Chr 24:10). That both Zechariah and Elizabeth descend from priestly lines underscores the thoroughly Levitical heritage of John\'s family. THEOLOGICAL: Luke\'s narrative begins in the temple with the old covenant priesthood, signaling that the new era of salvation emerges organically from within Israel\'s covenantal structures.',
        11: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: "Angelos kyriou" (ἄγγελος κυρίου) — "angel of the Lord" — denotes a member of the heavenly council dispatched on divine commission. The right side of the altar is the position of honor and authority. This is the first angelic visitation recorded in Israel since the prophetic era, breaking roughly four centuries of prophetic silence. TYPOLOGY: The appearance at the incense altar echoes the heavenly temple liturgy (Rev 8:3-4), connecting earthly worship with the divine council\'s activity.',
        15: 'GREEK: "Sikera" (σίκερα, Strong\'s G4608) is a Semitic loanword for fermented drink other than grape wine. TYPOLOGY: The prohibition of wine and strong drink echoes the Nazirite vow (Num 6:3) and specifically recalls the angelic announcement concerning Samson (Judg 13:4-7). John\'s filling with the Holy Spirit from the womb sets him apart as the eschatological prophet. THEOLOGICAL: The prenatal filling with the Spirit is unprecedented and signals the inbreaking of the messianic age.',
        17: 'TYPOLOGY: Direct allusion to Malachi 4:5-6 (LXX 3:22-23), identifying John with the eschatological Elijah who precedes the Day of the Lord. "To make ready for the Lord a people prepared" echoes Isa 40:3. THEOLOGICAL: The phrase "before him" (enōpion autou) is ambiguous — it could refer to going before the Lord God (v.16) or before the coming Messiah, creating a deliberate theological overlap between YHWH\'s visitation and the Messiah\'s coming.',
        19: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: Gabriel (Γαβριήλ, "mighty one of God") is one of the named angels who stands in the presence of God — a member of the inner divine council (cf. Dan 8:16; 9:21). "Ho parestēkōs enōpion tou theou" — "the one standing before God" — denotes his permanent station in the heavenly throne room. In Second Temple Jewish literature (1 Enoch 9:1; 40:9), Gabriel is one of four archangels with specific cosmic responsibilities.',
        25: 'TYPOLOGY: Elizabeth\'s language echoes the experience of barren matriarchs in Israel\'s history: Sarah (Gen 21:6-7), Rachel (Gen 30:23), and Hannah (1 Sam 1:19-20). The removal of "reproach" (oneidos, ὄνειδος) among humans parallels Rachel\'s exact words in Gen 30:23 LXX. Each barren-woman narrative in Scripture signals a pivotal moment in redemptive history.',
        31: 'GREEK: "Iēsoun" (Ἰησοῦν) — the Greek form of Hebrew Yehoshua/Yeshua, meaning "YHWH saves." TYPOLOGY: The annunciation pattern — angel appears, fear arises, divine message given, child named, destiny foretold — mirrors the pattern of Isaac (Gen 17-18), Samson (Judg 13), and Samuel (1 Sam 1). The naming of the child before conception signifies divine predetermination of his mission.',
        32: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Son of the Most High" (huios hypsistou) is a divine title with both Davidic royal (2 Sam 7:14; Ps 2:7) and divine-nature implications. "The Lord God shall give to him the throne of David his father" fulfills the Davidic covenant (2 Sam 7:12-16). TYPOLOGY: This verse weaves together the Nathan oracle, the royal psalms, and Daniel 7:14, presenting Jesus as the ultimate Davidic King whose enthronement is enacted by God himself.',
        33: 'THEOLOGICAL: "He shall reign over the house of Jacob unto the ages, and of his kingdom there shall be no end" directly fulfills Dan 7:14 and 2 Sam 7:13,16. The eternal, unending nature of this kingdom distinguishes it from all earthly monarchies and confirms Jesus as the promised Messiah whose dominion is absolute and everlasting.',
        35: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The Holy Spirit shall come upon you, and the power of the Most High shall overshadow you" — the verb "episkiazō" (ἐπισκιάζω, Strong\'s G1982) echoes the Shekinah glory overshadowing the tabernacle (Exod 40:35 LXX). The virginal conception is attributed to the direct creative action of the Spirit. "The holy one being born shall be called Son of God" — "dio kai" (therefore also) establishes a causal link between the Spirit\'s overshadowing and the designation "Son of God," though this title carries both messianic-royal and ontological weight. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The language of divine creative power descending parallels Gen 1:2 where the Spirit hovers over the waters, marking this as a new-creation event.',
        37: 'GREEK: "Ouk adynatēsei para tou theou pan rhēma" — literally "no word/thing from God shall be without power." "Rhēma" (ῥῆμα) means both "word" and "thing/matter," preserving the Hebrew dabar concept where God\'s spoken word is itself the effective power that accomplishes the thing spoken. TYPOLOGY: Direct echo of Gen 18:14 LXX, spoken concerning Sarah\'s miraculous conception of Isaac, linking Mary\'s situation to the foundational covenant promise.',
        38: 'THEOLOGICAL: Mary\'s self-designation as "doulē kyriou" (δούλη κυρίου, "handmaid of the Lord") expresses total submission to the divine will. Her "genoito" (γένοιτο, "let it be") is an optative of willing consent, contrasting with Zechariah\'s doubt. Mary\'s faith-response becomes the human instrument through which the Incarnation proceeds.',
        43: 'THEOLOGICAL: Elizabeth\'s exclamation "the mother of my Lord" (hē mētēr tou kyriou mou) is theologically momentous. "Kyrios mou" echoes Ps 110:1 LXX — "The Lord said to my Lord" — a key messianic text. Elizabeth, filled with the Holy Spirit, recognizes the unborn Jesus as her Lord, a confession of his messianic and divine identity even before his birth.',
        46: 'STRUCTURE: The Magnificat (vv.46-55) is a hymnic unit closely modeled on Hannah\'s Song (1 Sam 2:1-10). It follows a chiastic structure: personal praise (46-49), God\'s universal character (50-53), covenantal faithfulness to Israel (54-55). TYPOLOGY: Mary recapitulates and surpasses Hannah\'s role — as Hannah\'s barrenness gave way to Samuel who anointed kings, Mary\'s virginal conception brings forth the King himself.',
        51: 'THEOLOGICAL: The aorist tenses in vv.51-55 are prophetic aorists — speaking of future divine actions as already accomplished, reflecting the Hebrew prophetic perspective. "He has scattered the proud in the thought of their hearts" — "dianoiā kardias autōn" indicates that pride originates in the inner reasoning of the heart, and God\'s judgment addresses the root disposition. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The scattering of the proud echoes the divine council\'s judgment against the builders of Babel (Gen 11:8) and the overthrow of rebellious spiritual powers.',
        54: 'TYPOLOGY: "He has helped Israel his servant" — "paidos autou" (παιδὸς αὐτοῦ) echoes the Servant of the Lord language in Isaiah (Isa 41:8-9; 42:1; 44:1). Israel as God\'s "pais" (servant/child) connects to the Servant Songs, which find their ultimate fulfillment in the Messiah whom Mary now carries.',
        68: 'STRUCTURE: The Benedictus (vv.68-79) divides into two sections: God\'s redemption of Israel through the Davidic Messiah (68-75) and the prophetic destiny of John (76-79). THEOLOGICAL: "Epeskepsato" (ἐπεσκέψατο, "has visited") implies God\'s personal, gracious intervention — he has come to inspect, care for, and deliver his people. "Epoiēsen lytrōsin" — "wrought redemption" — uses sacrificial-economic language for God\'s liberating action.',
        69: 'TYPOLOGY: "Horn of salvation" (keras sōtērias) is drawn from the royal-messianic vocabulary of the OT (Ps 18:2; 132:17; 1 Sam 2:10). The horn symbolizes strength and royal power. "In the house of David his servant" confirms this as Davidic-messianic fulfillment — God raises up a mighty deliverer from David\'s lineage, fulfilling the covenant of 2 Sam 7.',
        76: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Prophet of the Most High" (prophētēs hypsistou) parallels Jesus\' title "Son of the Most High" (v.32), carefully distinguishing John\'s role as prophetic forerunner from Jesus\' identity as the divine Son. "You shall go before the face of the Lord" — "pro prosōpou kyriou" echoes Mal 3:1 and Isa 40:3, identifying John as the messenger preparing the way before YHWH himself, who comes in the person of the Messiah.',
        78: 'GREEK: "Anatolē ex hypsous" (ἀνατολὴ ἐξ ὕψους) — "Dayspring from on high" — is a richly layered messianic title. "Anatolē" (Strong\'s G395) means "rising" or "dawn" and translates Hebrew "tsemach" ("Branch") in the LXX of Jer 23:5, Zech 3:8, and 6:12, a recognized messianic designation. "Ex hypsous" — "from on high" — indicates heavenly origin. THEOLOGICAL: The Messiah is thus simultaneously the Davidic Branch growing from below and the divine Dayspring descending from above, uniting the earthly and heavenly dimensions of his person.',
        79: 'TYPOLOGY: "To shine upon those sitting in darkness and in the shadow of death" quotes Isa 9:1-2 (LXX), the great messianic prophecy of light dawning in Galilee. "Shadow of death" (skia thanatou) echoes Ps 23:4 and Ps 107:10. "To guide our feet into the way of peace" — "eirēnē" (εἰρήνη) translates Hebrew "shalom," encompassing not merely absence of conflict but the total restoration of right relationship with God, humanity, and creation.',
        80: 'HISTORICAL: John\'s time "in the wilderness" connects him to the prophetic tradition of desert preparation and possibly to communities like those at Qumran near the Dead Sea. "Anadeixis" (ἀνάδειξις, Strong\'s G323) is a hapax legomenon in the NT, meaning "public showing" or "commissioning" — a term used in Greco-Roman contexts for the formal installation of officials. THEOLOGICAL: The wilderness motif recalls Israel\'s formation in the desert and the prophetic expectation that God\'s definitive salvation would begin again from the wilderness (Isa 40:3; Hos 2:14).',
    },
    2: {
        1: 'HISTORICAL: Caesar Augustus (Octavian, reigned 27 BC–AD 14) issued imperial decrees (δόγμα, dógma, G1378) for census enrollments across the Roman Empire. Luke deliberately frames the birth of the true King of all the earth against the backdrop of the most powerful human ruler, showing that God\'s sovereign plan operates through and above imperial power. The term οἰκουμένη (oikouménē, G3625) refers to the entire inhabited world under Roman authority.',
        4: 'TYPOLOGY: Joseph\'s journey from Nazareth to Bethlehem fulfills Micah 5:2, which prophesied that from Bethlehem would come forth a ruler over Israel. The phrase "city of David" (πόλιν Δαυίδ) connects Jesus to the Davidic covenant (2 Sam 7:12-16). Luke emphasizes both "house" (οἶκος, oîkos, G3624) and "lineage" (πατριά, patriá, G3965) to establish royal genealogical legitimacy.',
        7: 'GREEK: πρωτότοκος (prōtótokos, G4416) means "firstborn," carrying both legal rights of primogeniture and deep theological resonance with Israel as God\'s firstborn (Exod 4:22) and the messianic Psalm 89:27. The κατάλυμα (katályma, G2646) is not a commercial inn (πανδοχεῖον) but a guest room or lodging space, possibly in a relative\'s home. TYPOLOGY: The manger (φάτνη, phátnē, G5336) where animals feed receives the Bread of Life; the one who will be the Lamb of God is laid where livestock are nourished.',
        9: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: The "angel of the Lord" (ἄγγελος κυρίου) employs a standard Septuagint formula for divine messengers acting as emissaries of the heavenly court. The "glory of the Lord" (δόξα κυρίου) shining around them recalls the kabod-YHWH theophanies of the Old Testament (Exod 24:16-17; Ezek 1:28). The shepherds\' response of great fear (ἐφοβήθησαν φόβον μέγαν) uses the cognate accusative construction typical of Semitic narrative style, emphasizing the overwhelming nature of the divine encounter.',
        11: 'THEOLOGICAL: This is one of the most theologically dense verses in the New Testament. Three titles converge: σωτήρ (sōtḗr, G4990, "Savior"), χριστός (Christós, G5547, "Christ/Anointed One"), and κύριος (kýrios, G2962, "Lord"). In the LXX, "Savior" is applied to God himself (Isa 45:21); "Christ" designates the anointed Davidic king; and "Lord" renders both \'adon and the divine Name. The angel\'s announcement declares that this infant is simultaneously God\'s salvation, the promised Davidic Messiah, and sovereign Lord. TYPOLOGY: "City of David" echoes the angelic promise to David in 2 Samuel 7, now fulfilled in the flesh.',
        13: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: The "multitude of the heavenly host" (πλῆθος στρατιᾶς οὐρανίου) is the divine army of God\'s celestial council. The term στρατιά (stratiá, G4756) means "army" or "host," directly corresponding to the Hebrew tsaba in "YHWH of Hosts" (YHWH Tseba\'ot). This is a momentary parting of the veil between the heavenly and earthly realms, as the divine council\'s worship becomes audible to human ears.',
        14: 'GREEK: The genitive εὐδοκίας (eudokías, G2107) modifies ἀνθρώποις, yielding "men of [his] good pleasure" or "men upon whom his favor rests"—not a general wish for goodwill but a declaration of God\'s electing favor. THEOLOGICAL: The hymn has a tripartite structure: glory directed upward to God in the highest, peace directed downward to earth, and the identifying mark of its recipients—those upon whom divine favor rests. This mirrors the divine council\'s role of declaring the decrees of God.',
        22: 'HISTORICAL: The purification refers to the Levitical requirements of Lev 12:1-8, where a mother was ceremonially unclean for forty days after bearing a male child. Luke says "their purification" (αὐτῶν, autōn—plural), possibly including Joseph in the broader family purification or reflecting the presentation rite. THEOLOGICAL: The verb παραστῆσαι (parastēsai, "to present") indicates formal consecration before the Lord, connecting to the firstborn consecration law of Exodus 13:2, 12.',
        23: 'TYPOLOGY: The quotation is from Exodus 13:2, 12 (LXX). Every firstborn male belongs to God as a memorial of the Passover deliverance. Jesus as the firstborn is consecrated to the Lord, but uniquely he is the Lord to whom all firstborn belong. The one being presented is the very God to whom the presentation is made—a profound Christological irony Luke embeds in the narrative.',
        26: 'THEOLOGICAL: The phrase "the Christ of the Lord" (τὸν χριστὸν κυρίου) echoes the LXX expression christos kyriou, "the Lord\'s Anointed" (1 Sam 2:10; Ps 2:2; Lam 4:20). The Holy Spirit\'s revelation (κεχρηματισμένον, from chrēmatízō, G5537—a divine oracle or warning) to Simeon that he would not see death before seeing the Messiah places him in the prophetic tradition of those who waited for God\'s eschatological king. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The Spirit functions here as the divine agent mediating the council\'s decree to a faithful human.',
        29: 'GREEK: δέσποτα (despóta, G1203) is the vocative of despótēs, meaning "Master" or "Sovereign Lord"—a term denoting absolute ownership, used of God in contexts of sovereign authority (Acts 4:24; Rev 6:10). It differs from κύριος in emphasizing dominion over slaves or servants. The verb ἀπολύεις (apolýeis, "you release/dismiss") pictures a sentinel being relieved from duty, or a slave being set free. TYPOLOGY: Simeon\'s Nunc Dimittis echoes Isaiah 40:5 and 52:10, where God\'s salvation is revealed before all nations.',
        32: 'THEOLOGICAL: φῶς εἰς ἀποκάλυψιν ἐθνῶν (phōs eis apokálypsin ethnōn)—"a light for revelation to the nations"—draws directly from Isaiah 42:6 and 49:6, the Servant Songs, where the Servant of YHWH is appointed as a light to the Gentiles. The pairing with "glory of your people Israel" establishes the dual scope of the Messiah\'s mission: universal revelation to the nations and the consummation of Israel\'s hope. TYPOLOGY: Jesus fulfills the role of the Isaianic Servant whose light reaches beyond Israel to all peoples.',
        34: 'THEOLOGICAL: Simeon\'s oracle to Mariam is both messianic and ominous. The phrase εἰς πτῶσιν καὶ ἀνάστασιν (eis ptōsin kai anástasin, "for fall and rising") indicates that Jesus will be the point of division—a stone of stumbling and a rock of rising (Isa 8:14; 28:16). The σημεῖον ἀντιλεγόμενον (sēmeîon antilegómenon, "sign spoken against") foreshadows the rejection of Jesus by the religious establishment and ultimately the cross.',
        35: 'GREEK: ῥομφαία (rhomphaía, G4501) denotes a large, broad sword—not the common μάχαιρα—suggesting devastating penetration of grief. TYPOLOGY: The sword piercing Mariam\'s soul foreshadows her witness of the crucifixion (John 19:25-27). The purpose clause ὅπως ἂν ἀποκαλυφθῶσιν ("so that may be revealed") indicates that Jesus\' ministry and death will serve as the ultimate apocalyptic disclosure of human hearts—what people truly believe will be exposed by how they respond to him.',
        38: 'GREEK: ἀνθωμολογεῖτο (anthōmologéomai, G437) is a NT hapax legomenon meaning "to give thanks" or "to confess praise in return." It appears in the LXX (e.g., Ps 79:13 LXX) but occurs only here in the New Testament. THEOLOGICAL: Anna speaks about the child to all those "awaiting the redemption (λύτρωσιν, lýtrōsin, G3085) of Jerusalem," a phrase rooted in prophetic expectation of God\'s eschatological deliverance of his people (Isa 52:9). Both Simeon and Anna function as prophetic witnesses confirming the child\'s messianic identity.',
        40: 'THEOLOGICAL: Luke summarizes Jesus\' childhood growth with language echoing the description of Samuel (1 Sam 2:26). The verb ἐκραταιοῦτο (ekrataioûto, "became strong") and the phrase "filled with wisdom" (πληρούμενον σοφίᾳ) indicate the genuine human development of the incarnate Son. The grace of God (χάρις θεοῦ) being "upon him" (ἐπ\' αὐτό) points to the Father\'s continual favor resting on the child. TYPOLOGY: As Samuel grew in the temple precincts and found favor with God and men, so Jesus grows as the greater prophet-priest-king.',
        49: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus\' first recorded words in Luke are a declaration of divine sonship: "in the things of my Father" (ἐν τοῖς τοῦ πατρός μου). The phrase τοῦ πατρός μου ("my Father") is striking on the lips of a twelve-year-old, distinguishing his relationship to God from any other. The verb δεῖ (deî, G1163, "it is necessary") expresses divine compulsion and will appear throughout Luke\'s Gospel at critical moments of Jesus\' mission (Luke 4:43; 9:22; 24:7, 26, 44). Even at age twelve, Jesus is aware of his unique vocation and identity as the Son of God.',
        52: 'GREEK: προέκοπτεν (proékopten, from prokóptō, G4298) means "to advance" or "to cut forward," like a pioneer cutting a path. TYPOLOGY: This summary statement parallels 1 Samuel 2:26 almost verbatim in the LXX, completing the Samuel typology Luke has woven throughout the infancy narrative. Jesus is the greater Samuel—prophet, intercessor, and the one who will anoint himself as both priest and king. The fourfold advance—wisdom, stature, and grace before both God and men—affirms the full, authentic humanity of the incarnate Word.',
    },
    3: {
        1: 'HISTORICAL: Luke anchors the gospel narrative in precise Roman chronology — the fifteenth year of Tiberius Caesar places this around AD 28-29. The sixfold political designation (emperor, governor, three tetrarchs, and high priests) situates the divine word breaking into a specific moment of world history, emphasizing that God acts within real, datable events. The mention of multiple rulers also subtly portrays the fractured political landscape of Israel under foreign domination.',
        2: 'GREEK: The phrase ἐγένετο ῥῆμα θεοῦ (egeneto rhēma theou, "the word of God came") echoes the LXX prophetic formula (cf. Jer 1:1; Hos 1:1; Joel 1:1), deliberately placing John in the line of the Old Testament prophets. THEOLOGICAL: The dual high priesthood of Annas and Caiaphas reflects a corrupted priestly office — Annas had been deposed by Rome but retained power behind Caiaphas, pointing to the broken state of Israel\'s religious leadership into which God\'s word now irrupts.',
        3: 'GREEK: βάπτισμα μετανοίας (baptisma metanoias) — "baptism of repentance." Metanoia (Strong\'s G3341) means a fundamental change of mind and direction, not mere remorse. The genitive μετανοίας is a genitive of characterization: this baptism is defined by and expresses repentance. TYPOLOGY: The Jordan river setting evokes Israel\'s original crossing into the Promised Land (Josh 3), suggesting a new entry into covenant faithfulness.',
        4: 'TYPOLOGY: The quotation from Isaiah 40:3-5 (LXX) originally addressed Israel\'s return from Babylonian exile, the preparation of a highway for God himself to travel. Luke applies this to John preparing the way for the Lord Jesus, identifying Jesus with the coming of YHWH himself. STRUCTURE: Luke extends the Isaiah quotation further than Matthew or Mark, continuing through verse 6 to include "all flesh shall see the salvation of God," reflecting Luke\'s universal emphasis.',
        6: 'THEOLOGICAL: Luke alone among the Synoptics includes this final line from Isaiah 40:5 LXX — καὶ ὄψεται πᾶσα σὰρξ τὸ σωτήριον τοῦ θεοῦ ("and all flesh shall see the salvation of God"). This universalism is a key Lukan theme: the salvation brought by the Messiah is not for Israel alone but for all nations (cf. Luke 2:30-32; Acts 28:28). GREEK: σωτήριον (sōtērion, Strong\'s G4992) — "salvation" in a substantive, concrete sense, denoting God\'s saving act made visible.',
        7: 'GREEK: Γεννήματα ἐχιδνῶν (gennēmata echidnōn) — "offspring of vipers." Génnēma (Strong\'s G1081) means "that which is begotten/produced," emphasizing lineage and nature. The viper metaphor implies a poisonous and dangerous nature inherited from their spiritual parentage. THEOLOGICAL: John\'s warning subverts the assumption that ethnic descent guarantees divine favor, a theme Jesus will continue throughout Luke\'s Gospel.',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: John demolishes the presumption that Abrahamic descent automatically secures covenant standing. God\'s power to raise children from stones (lithōn/lithōn playing on a possible Aramaic wordplay with "children"/benayya and "stones"/abnayya) demonstrates divine sovereignty over covenant membership. This anticipates the inclusion of Gentiles in the people of God (cf. Rom 4:16-17; Gal 3:7-9).',
        9: 'TYPOLOGY: The imagery of the axe at the root of the trees and the fruitless tree cast into fire is an eschatological judgment motif. This echoes Isaiah 10:33-34 where God hews down the forest of the proud. The present tense κεῖται ("is laid") indicates the imminence of judgment — the axe is already positioned, not merely approaching.',
        15: 'GREEK: διαλογιζομένων (dialogizomenōn, Strong\'s G1260) — "reasoning, deliberating" — denotes inner dialogue and weighing of possibilities. The people\'s messianic expectation reflects the intense eschatological hope of Second Temple Judaism. HISTORICAL: Various messianic expectations circulated in this period, including a royal Davidic messiah, a priestly messiah (as at Qumran), and a prophetic figure like Moses (Deut 18:15).',
        16: 'THEOLOGICAL: John draws a sharp contrast between his water baptism and the coming One\'s baptism ἐν πνεύματι ἁγίῳ καὶ πυρί ("in the Holy Spirit and fire"). The language of unworthiness to loose a sandal strap signifies that John considers himself lower than a slave in relation to the Coming One. TYPOLOGY: The dual baptism of Spirit and fire echoes the prophetic promises of purification (Mal 3:2-3; Isa 4:4) and the outpouring of the Spirit (Joel 2:28-29), fulfilled at Pentecost (Acts 2:3-4) where tongues "as of fire" appear with the Spirit.',
        17: 'GREEK: πτύον (ptyon, Strong\'s G4425) — "winnowing fork," used to toss threshed grain into the air so wind separates wheat from chaff. ἄσβεστος (asbestos, Strong\'s G762) — "unquenchable," describing the finality and inescapability of eschatological judgment. THEOLOGICAL: This verse presents Christ as the eschatological Judge who separates the righteous from the unrighteous — a function attributed to God alone in the Old Testament (cf. Ps 1:4-6; Mal 4:1).',
        21: 'THEOLOGICAL: Luke uniquely notes that Jesus was praying when heaven opened — prayer accompanies every major turning point in Luke\'s Gospel (Luke 6:12; 9:18, 28-29; 22:41-44). The opening of heaven signifies the rupture of the barrier between the divine and human realms, recalling Isaiah 64:1: "Oh, that you would rend the heavens and come down." STRUCTURE: Luke places the baptism after John\'s imprisonment narrative (vv.19-20), de-emphasizing the baptizer and focusing on the divine attestation of Jesus.',
        22: 'THEOLOGICAL: The voice from heaven combines Psalm 2:7 ("You are my Son") — a royal enthronement psalm — with Isaiah 42:1 ("in whom my soul delights") — the Servant of the Lord. This dual allusion identifies Jesus simultaneously as the Davidic King and the Suffering Servant. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The heavenly voice constitutes a divine decree of sonship, echoing the council decrees of Psalm 2 where God installs his King on Zion. The bodily descent of the Spirit (σωματικῷ εἴδει, sōmatikō eidei — "in bodily form") emphasizes the reality and visibility of this anointing.',
        23: 'GREEK: ὡς ἐνομίζετο (hōs enomizeto) — "as was supposed/reckoned by custom." The verb νομίζω (nomizō, Strong\'s G3543) implies conventional assumption, not legal or biological certainty. Luke thus carefully qualifies the Joseph-Jesus relationship. HISTORICAL: Beginning at about thirty years of age echoes David\'s age at the start of his reign (2 Sam 5:4) and the age at which Levites began temple service (Num 4:3), framing Jesus as both King and Priest.',
        31: 'TYPOLOGY: Luke traces Jesus\' line through Nathan, son of David (2 Sam 5:14), rather than through Solomon as in Matthew\'s genealogy. This traces a different Davidic line, possibly through Mary\'s lineage, and avoids the curse on Jeconiah\'s royal line (Jer 22:30). Nathan\'s line nonetheless establishes Jesus firmly within the house of David, fulfilling the Davidic covenant promise (2 Sam 7:12-16).',
        38: 'THEOLOGICAL: Luke traces the genealogy all the way back to τοῦ Ἀδὰμ τοῦ θεοῦ — "of Adam, of God." This is the theological climax of the genealogy: Jesus is not merely son of Abraham (as in Matthew) but son of Adam, and ultimately Son of God. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The designation of Adam as "of God" (τοῦ θεοῦ) frames human origin in direct divine relationship and sonship. By tracing Jesus back to Adam and to God, Luke establishes Jesus as the representative of all humanity — the last Adam (cf. Rom 5:14; 1 Cor 15:45) — whose redemptive work extends to every nation, not Israel alone.',
    },
    4: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Plērēs" (πλήρης, G4134) meaning "full, complete" — denotes not partial but total saturation by the Holy Spirit. The passive voice of "ēgeto" (ἤγετο, imperfect of ágō) indicates Jesus was continually being led by the Spirit, not acting on his own initiative. TYPOLOGY: Jesus\'s forty days in the wilderness recapitulates Israel\'s forty years of wilderness testing (Deut 8:2), yet where Israel failed, the faithful Son succeeds.',
        2: 'GREEK: "Peirazomenos" (πειραζόμενος, G3985) is a present passive participle — the temptation was ongoing throughout the forty days, not confined to the three episodes that follow. "Diabolos" (διάβολος, G1228) literally means "slanderer" or "one who casts across," i.e., the accuser who throws charges (cf. Rev 12:10). TYPOLOGY: The forty-day fast parallels Moses on Sinai (Exod 34:28) and Elijah\'s journey to Horeb (1 Kgs 19:8), positioning Jesus as the prophet greater than both.',
        3: 'THEOLOGICAL: The conditional "Ei" (εἰ) with the indicative assumes the condition as true for the sake of argument — "If you are the Son of God (and you are)..." The devil does not question Jesus\'s identity but challenges him to exercise divine prerogatives outside the Father\'s will. This is a test of obedient sonship, not of ontological identity.',
        5: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: The devil\'s claim to show "all the kingdoms of the inhabited world" (oikoumenē, G3625) in a "stigmē chronou" (στιγμῇ χρόνου, a point of time) implies a supernatural vision. The term "oikoumenē" refers specifically to the civilized, governed world — the political sphere over which the devil claims delegated authority (cf. John 12:31; Eph 6:12; Dan 10:13,20).',
        6: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Paradedotai" (παραδέδοται, G3860, perfect passive) — "it has been delivered over to me" — implies the devil claims a prior bestowal of cosmic authority. This language echoes the Deuteronomy 32 worldview where God allotted the nations to the sons of God (LXX Deut 32:8-9), some of whom became corrupt. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The devil\'s claim is not entirely false — he exercises delegated, usurped authority over fallen world systems — but it is deceptive in implying absolute and rightful ownership. Jesus does not dispute the claim but refuses the terms.',
        8: 'GREEK: Jesus quotes Deuteronomy 6:13 (LXX), using "Kyrion" (Κύριον) for the divine name and "latreuō" (λατρεύω, G3000), which denotes cultic, sacred service — worship reserved for God alone. TYPOLOGY: Where Israel worshipped the golden calf and bowed to foreign gods in the wilderness, the true Son of God refuses all idolatry even when offered all earthly power.',
        12: 'GREEK: "Ekpeiraseis" (ἐκπειράσεις, G1598) is an intensified form of "peirazō" — to test thoroughly, to put to the ultimate test. Jesus quotes Deuteronomy 6:16 (LXX), referencing the incident at Massah (Exod 17:1-7). THEOLOGICAL: Jesus refuses to manipulate God into proving his faithfulness, demonstrating the trust that Israel failed to show.',
        13: 'GREEK: "Achri kairou" (ἄχρι καιροῦ) — "until an opportune/appointed time" — "kairos" (G2540) denotes not mere chronological time but a strategic, decisive season. THEOLOGICAL: Luke uniquely emphasizes this temporary withdrawal; the devil returns at the Passion (Luke 22:3, 53), suggesting the cross is the supreme confrontation between Jesus and the powers of darkness.',
        18: 'GREEK: "Echrisen" (ἔχρισεν, G5548, from chriō) — "he anointed me" — is the verbal root from which "Christos" (Christ/Anointed One) derives. Jesus is identifying himself as the Anointed One of Isaiah 61:1-2. TYPOLOGY: The anointing language evokes the threefold anointing of prophet, priest, and king in the OT. Jesus\'s reading conflates Isaiah 61:1-2a with Isaiah 58:6 ("to send forth the oppressed in deliverance"), showing a deliberate hermeneutical act. THEOLOGICAL: The "captives" (aichmalōtois) and "oppressed" (tethrausmenous) carry both physical and spiritual connotations — liberation from sin, Satan, and systemic injustice.',
        19: 'GREEK: "Eniautos kyriou dektos" (ἐνιαυτὸν κυρίου δεκτόν) — "the acceptable year of the Lord" — echoes the Jubilee legislation of Leviticus 25, when debts were cancelled, slaves freed, and land restored. TYPOLOGY: Jesus stops reading mid-sentence in Isaiah 61:2, omitting "and the day of vengeance of our God." This deliberate omission announces the era of grace and Jubilee fulfillment while deferring the day of judgment to his return (cf. Acts 17:31; Rev 19).',
        21: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Sēmeron" (Σήμερον, G4594) — "Today" — carries immense eschatological weight. The perfect tense "peplērōtai" (πεπλήρωται, G4137) indicates that the Scripture stands fulfilled in the present with abiding results. Jesus does not say "I will fulfill" but declares the fulfillment accomplished in his very speaking. This is the programmatic declaration of Jesus\'s ministry in Luke.',
        26: 'HISTORICAL: Zarephath (Sarepta) was a Phoenician town in the territory of Sidon — pagan Gentile territory. TYPOLOGY: Jesus\'s appeal to Elijah being sent to a Gentile widow (1 Kgs 17:8-24) and Elisha cleansing Naaman the Syrian (2 Kgs 5:1-14) foreshadows the inclusion of the Gentiles in God\'s salvation. This teaching provokes the rage of verse 28 precisely because it implies God\'s grace transcends ethnic Israel.',
        29: 'GREEK: "Katakrēmnisai" (κατακρημνίσαι, G2630) is a hapax legomenon in the NT — "to throw down a precipice/cliff." HISTORICAL: Nazareth sits on a ridge overlooking the Jezreel Valley. The attempt to cast Jesus from the cliff edge anticipates the violent rejection that culminates at Calvary. TYPOLOGY: The rejected prophet motif (v. 24) reaches its climax; like Joseph rejected by his brothers, Jesus is expelled from his own people only to become their deliverer.',
        30: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Dielthōn dia mesou autōn" (διελθὼν διὰ μέσου αὐτῶν) — "having passed through the midst of them" — implies a supernatural or sovereign departure. His hour had not yet come (cf. John 7:30; 8:59). Jesus\'s authority over his own destiny is evident even in the face of murderous intent.',
        34: 'GREEK: "Ea" (Ἔα) is an interjection of alarm or dismay — "Ha!" or "Ah!" The demon uses the plural "us" (hēmas), possibly speaking for the entire demonic realm. "Ho hagios tou theou" (ὁ ἅγιος τοῦ θεοῦ) — "the Holy One of God" — is a messianic title expressing Jesus\'s unique consecration and divine identity. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The demon recognizes Jesus\'s authority within the spiritual hierarchy. The question "Have you come to destroy us?" acknowledges Jesus\'s eschatological mission to overthrow the rebellious spiritual powers (cf. 1 John 3:8; Col 2:15).',
        41: 'THEOLOGICAL: The demons declare both "You are the Son of God" and (by Luke\'s editorial comment) that they "knew him to be the Christ." Luke equates the titles — Son of God and Christ are two aspects of the same identity. Jesus silences them not because their confession is false but because the messianic secret must unfold on God\'s terms, not through demonic proclamation. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The unclean spirits possess accurate theological knowledge of Jesus\'s identity as the Anointed King, yet their knowledge does not produce saving faith — it produces terror (cf. James 2:19).',
        43: 'GREEK: "Euangelisasthai" (εὐαγγελίσασθαι, G2097) — "to proclaim good tidings" — is a key Lukan term linking Jesus\'s mission to Isaiah\'s herald of salvation (Isa 52:7; 61:1). "Apestalēn" (ἀπεστάλην, G649, aorist passive) — "I was sent forth" — emphasizes divine commissioning; Jesus is the sent one par excellence, the Apostle of the Father (cf. Heb 3:1). THEOLOGICAL: The "kingdom of God" (basileian tou theou) is the central content of Jesus\'s proclamation — God\'s sovereign reign breaking into the present age through Jesus\'s person and ministry.',
    },
    5: {
        1: 'GREEK: The phrase ἐπικεῖσθαι (epíkeisthai, "to press upon") conveys the crowd physically crowding around Jesus. "The word of God" (τὸν λόγον τοῦ θεοῦ) is Luke\'s characteristic way of describing Jesus\'s teaching, identifying it as divine revelation. Lake Gennesaret is the Sea of Galilee (cf. Matt 14:34; Mark 6:53).',
        5: 'GREEK: Ἐπιστάτα (epistatá, "Master") is a term unique to Luke among the Gospels (Strong\'s G1988), used only by disciples addressing Jesus. It denotes one who stands over or commands—a superintendent or overseer. Simon\'s obedience despite failure ("upon your word," ἐπὶ τῷ ῥήματί σου) demonstrates nascent faith responding to divine authority.',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: Peter\'s response echoes Isaiah\'s reaction before the holy God (Isa 6:5). The recognition of sinfulness in the presence of divine power reveals that this miraculous catch functions as a theophany—a manifestation of God\'s presence through Jesus. Peter addresses him as κύριε (kýrie, "Lord"), which in this context transcends mere respectful address.',
        10: 'GREEK: ζωγρῶν (zōgrōn, "catching alive," Strong\'s G2221) is a striking term meaning literally "to take alive" or "to capture for life." In classical usage it described taking prisoners of war alive. Jesus redefines the fisherman\'s vocation: from catching fish unto death to catching humans unto life. TYPOLOGY: The miraculous catch prefigures the apostolic mission and the great ingathering of the nations (cf. John 21:1-14; Ezek 47:9-10).',
        13: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus touching a leper violates Levitical purity boundaries (Lev 13:45-46), yet rather than Jesus becoming unclean, the leper is made clean. This reveals Jesus\'s authority over the ritual system itself—holiness flows from him and overpowers impurity. The immediacy (εὐθέως, euthéōs) emphasizes divine power.',
        14: 'TYPOLOGY: The command to show himself to the priest and offer according to what Moses commanded (Lev 14:1-32) serves as "a testimony to them" (εἰς μαρτύριον αὐτοῖς). Jesus upholds the Mosaic law while simultaneously demonstrating that he possesses the authority that the priestly system was designed to mediate. The cleansed leper becomes living evidence that the messianic age has dawned (cf. Isa 35:5-6; Matt 11:5).',
        17: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The power of the Lord was present for him to heal" (δύναμις κυρίου ἦν εἰς τὸ ἰᾶσθαι αὐτόν)—κυρίου here likely refers to YHWH, indicating that divine power was operative through Jesus. Luke uniquely emphasizes this divine empowerment. HISTORICAL: The presence of Pharisees and teachers of the law from every village of Galilee, Judea, and Jerusalem indicates that Jesus\'s ministry had attracted official scrutiny from the religious establishment.',
        20: 'THEOLOGICAL: The passive "are forgiven" (ἀφέωνται, perfect passive indicative) is a divine passive—God is the implied agent. Yet Jesus speaks this forgiveness directly, claiming to enact what only God can do. This sets up the confrontation in v.21 and establishes Jesus\'s divine prerogative.',
        21: 'THEOLOGICAL: The scribes and Pharisees reason correctly that God alone can forgive sins (cf. Isa 43:25; Ps 103:3). Their logic is sound; their error is failing to recognize who stands before them. Jesus does not correct their theology about forgiveness being God\'s prerogative—instead he demonstrates that he possesses that very prerogative. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The claim to forgive sins places Jesus in the role of the divine Judge, a function belonging to the God of Israel alone in Second Temple Jewish theology.',
        24: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The Son of Man" (ὁ υἱὸς τοῦ ἀνθρώπου) is Jesus\'s preferred self-designation, drawn from Daniel 7:13-14 where the "one like a son of man" receives authority, glory, and an everlasting kingdom from the Ancient of Days. Jesus claims that this heavenly authority to forgive sins operates "upon the earth" (ἐπὶ τῆς γῆς)—the eschatological kingdom is breaking into the present age through his person. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The Son of Man in Daniel 7 receives dominion from the throne of God; Jesus enacts that dominion here by forgiving sins and commanding healing.',
        26: 'GREEK: ἔκστασις (ékstasis, Strong\'s G1611) denotes more than mere surprise—it is a displacement of the mind, an overwhelmed state before the numinous. παράδοξα (parádoxa, "extraordinary things," hapax legomenon in NT) literally means "beyond opinion" or "contrary to expectation"—things that exceed all human categories of understanding.',
        32: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus\'s mission statement echoes the prophetic tradition of God\'s pursuit of the lost (Ezek 34:16; Hos 6:6). "Repentance" (μετάνοια, metánoia) signifies not mere regret but a fundamental reorientation of mind and life toward God. Jesus defines his messianic vocation not as confirming the righteous but as reclaiming sinners.',
        34: 'TYPOLOGY: "Sons of the bridechamber" (τοὺς υἱοὺς τοῦ νυμφῶνος) designates wedding guests. Jesus identifies himself as the bridegroom, a title reserved for YHWH in the OT prophets (Isa 62:5; Hos 2:16-20; Jer 2:2). This is an implicit divine claim: God\'s covenant marriage to his people is being consummated in Jesus\'s presence. The coming "taking away" (ἀπαρθῇ, v.35) foreshadows his death.',
        36: 'THEOLOGICAL: The twin parables of the patch and wineskins declare that Jesus\'s ministry is not a reform of the old covenant system but the arrival of something radically new. The "new garment" and "new wine" represent the kingdom of God breaking in through Jesus. Attempting to contain the new reality within old structures will destroy both. STRUCTURE: Luke uniquely includes the detail that the new garment is torn, emphasizing double loss—the old is not helped and the new is ruined.',
        39: 'GREEK: χρηστός (chrēstós, "good, pleasant, kind"; some manuscripts read χρηστότερος, "better") describes the old wine. This verse, unique to Luke, acknowledges the human tendency to prefer the familiar over the new. THEOLOGICAL: Jesus does not condemn those who prefer "the old" but recognizes the difficulty of receiving the new thing God is doing. This serves as a warning about the resistance his message will face from those comfortable with existing religious structures.',
    },
    6: {
        1: 'TYPOLOGY: The grain-plucking incident echoes 1 Samuel 21:1-6, where David and his men ate the consecrated bread. Jesus draws a direct parallel between David\'s authority to override ceremonial law in necessity and his own authority as the greater David, the Anointed King. GREEK: σπορίμων (sporimōn, "sown fields/grainfields") appears also in Matt 12:1 and Mark 2:23 in the same Sabbath controversy.',
        4: 'TYPOLOGY: The "bread of the Presence" (ἄρτους τῆς προθέσεως, artous tēs protheseōs) refers to the twelve loaves set before God\'s face in the tabernacle (Lev 24:5-9). Jesus\' argument from the lesser to the greater implies that his authority exceeds that of David, and that mercy and human need transcend ceremonial regulation (cf. 1 Sam 21:1-6; Hos 6:6).',
        5: 'THEOLOGICAL: The claim "Lord of the Sabbath" (Κύριός ἐστιν τοῦ σαββάτου ὁ υἱὸς τοῦ ἀνθρώπου) is a breathtaking assertion of divine prerogative, since in the OT God himself instituted the Sabbath (Gen 2:2-3; Exod 20:8-11). By claiming lordship over it, the Son of Man asserts authority equal to the Creator. GREEK: Κύριος (kyrios, Strong\'s G2962) here carries the full weight of sovereign authority, not merely "master" in a social sense.',
        9: 'GREEK: ἀγαθοποιῆσαι (agathopoiēsai, "to do good") and κακοποιῆσαι (kakopoiēsai, "to do evil") are compound infinitives contrasting active goodness with active harm. Jesus reframes the Sabbath question: inaction in the face of suffering is itself evil. The parallel term ψυχὴν σῶσαι (psychēn sōsai, "to save a soul/life") elevates the stakes beyond mere halakhic debate (cf. Mark 3:4).',
        12: 'THEOLOGICAL: Luke uniquely records that Jesus spent the entire night in prayer (διανυκτερεύων ἐν τῇ προσευχῇ τοῦ θεοῦ) before choosing the Twelve. GREEK: διανυκτερεύων (dianyktereuōn, Strong\'s G1273) is a NT hapax legomenon, meaning "to spend the whole night." The phrase τῇ προσευχῇ τοῦ θεοῦ could mean "the prayer of God" (prayer directed to God) or possibly "the place of prayer to God." This night of prayer precedes the most consequential selection of leaders in redemptive history.',
        13: 'THEOLOGICAL: The choosing of twelve apostles (ἀποστόλους, apostolous, "sent ones") deliberately mirrors the twelve tribes of Israel, signaling that Jesus is reconstituting Israel around himself as its King and center. GREEK: ἐκλεξάμενος (eklexamenos, "having chosen out") is a middle voice participle, emphasizing Jesus\' personal, deliberate selection (cf. John 15:16).',
        17: 'STRUCTURE: Luke\'s "Sermon on the Plain" (vv. 17-49) parallels Matthew\'s Sermon on the Mount (Matt 5-7) but is set on a "level place" (τόπου πεδινοῦ). The geographic detail may carry theological weight: Jesus descends to meet the people where they are, in contrast to Moses ascending Sinai. HISTORICAL: The mention of Tyre and Sidon indicates Gentile regions, showing Jesus\' fame extending beyond Jewish territories.',
        20: 'THEOLOGICAL: Luke\'s Beatitudes are in the second person ("Blessed are you") and directed specifically at the disciples, whereas Matthew\'s are in the third person. Luke\'s version is starkly material—"the poor" (οἱ πτωχοί) without Matthew\'s qualifier "in spirit"—emphasizing God\'s concrete eschatological reversal. TYPOLOGY: This echoes the Magnificat of Mary (Luke 1:52-53) and the theme of divine reversal found throughout the OT prophets (Isa 61:1-2; 1 Sam 2:7-8).',
        22: 'GREEK: ἀφορίσωσιν (aphorisōsin, "they separate/exclude you") likely refers to excommunication from the synagogue, a practice attested in Second Temple Judaism. HISTORICAL: Being "separated" and having one\'s name "cast out as evil" (ἐκβάλωσιν τὸ ὄνομα ὑμῶν ὡς πονηρόν) reflects the experience of Jewish Christians expelled from synagogues, a situation becoming acute by the time Luke writes.',
        26: 'TYPOLOGY: The parallel between the false prophets (ψευδοπροφήταις) and those whom "all men speak well of" inverts the prophetic pattern of the OT. True prophets like Jeremiah, Elijah, and Micaiah were persecuted and reviled (1 Kgs 22:8; Jer 38:6), while false prophets enjoyed popular acclaim (Jer 5:31; Mic 2:11). Jesus establishes a pattern: authentic kingdom proclamation invites opposition.',
        35: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Sons of the Most High" (υἱοὶ Ὑψίστου) is a significant divine council term. DIVINE_COUNCIL: In the OT, "sons of the Most High" (בְּנֵי עֶלְיוֹן, cf. Ps 82:6) refers to divine beings in God\'s heavenly assembly. Jesus applies this title to his followers who emulate the Father\'s character—kindness to the ungrateful and evil—thereby elevating believers to a status associated with the heavenly council. GREEK: Ὑψίστου (Hypsistou, Strong\'s G5310) is the Greek rendering of Hebrew Elyon, a name for God emphasizing his supreme sovereignty over all other powers.',
        36: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Be merciful as your Father is merciful" (οἰκτίρμονες καθὼς ὁ πατὴρ ὑμῶν οἰκτίρμων ἐστίν) parallels the imitatio Dei principle. GREEK: οἰκτίρμων (oiktirmōn, Strong\'s G3629) denotes deep compassion from the bowels, echoing the Hebrew רַחוּם (rachum), used of God in Exod 34:6 and Ps 103:8. Where Matthew 5:48 says "perfect" (τέλειος), Luke uses "merciful," grounding divine imitation in compassionate action rather than abstract moral completeness.',
        38: 'GREEK: The fourfold description—καλὸν πεπιεσμένον σεσαλευμένον ὑπερεκχυννόμενον (good, pressed down, shaken together, overflowing)—employs marketplace grain-measuring imagery. HISTORICAL: In ancient grain markets, a generous merchant would press down the grain, shake the container to settle it, and let it overflow. The "bosom" (κόλπον) refers to the fold of the garment used as a pouch for carrying goods. Jesus portrays God\'s generosity as extravagantly exceeding any human measure.',
        40: 'GREEK: κατηρτισμένος (katērtismenos, "fully trained/perfected," Strong\'s G2675) is a perfect passive participle meaning "completely equipped" or "restored to proper condition." The term is used in medical Greek for setting broken bones. The goal of discipleship is not to surpass the teacher but to be conformed to him—a principle with profound Christological implications (cf. Rom 8:29; Eph 4:12-13).',
        46: 'THEOLOGICAL: The doubled vocative "Lord, Lord" (Κύριε κύριε) intensifies the claim of allegiance while exposing its emptiness without obedience. Jesus asserts that authentic recognition of his lordship requires corresponding action, not mere verbal confession (cf. Matt 7:21). The very fact that he demands obedience as the criterion of relationship implicitly claims divine authority.',
        48: 'TYPOLOGY: The image of building on rock recalls the OT theme of God as the Rock (צוּר) of Israel (Deut 32:4; 2 Sam 22:2; Ps 18:2). GREEK: ἐβάθυνεν (ebathynen, "he went deep") is unique to Luke\'s version and emphasizes the deliberate, costly effort of obedient faith. The flood (πλημμύρης, plēmmyrēs—a NT hapax legomenon) represents eschatological testing. STRUCTURE: The parable forms the climactic conclusion to the sermon, presenting two destinies based on response to Jesus\' words.',
        49: 'GREEK: ῥῆγμα (rhēgma, Strong\'s G4485) is a NT hapax legomenon meaning "ruin" or "wreckage," derived from ῥήγνυμι ("to break/burst"). The word emphasizes total catastrophic collapse. THEOLOGICAL: The contrast between the two builders is not between hearing and not hearing, but between hearing-and-doing versus hearing-and-not-doing. Both men heard the words of Jesus; the difference is obedience. The "great ruin" warns of eschatological judgment for those who acknowledge Jesus verbally but refuse his lordship in practice.',
    },
    7: {
        2: 'GREEK: The term ἔντιμος (entimos, "dear/honored") indicates this was no ordinary slave but one held in high esteem. The word ἑκατοντάρχης (hekatontarchēs) denotes a Roman officer commanding a century (approximately 80-100 soldiers). HISTORICAL: Roman centurions stationed in Galilee were typically part of Herod Antipas\'s forces modeled on Roman organization, though some may have served Rome directly.',
        5: 'HISTORICAL: A Gentile centurion who built a synagogue for the Jewish community represents the phenomenon of "God-fearers" — Gentiles attracted to Judaism without full conversion. Archaeological evidence from Capernaum confirms the presence of a notable synagogue. THEOLOGICAL: This foreshadows the inclusion of Gentiles in the kingdom, a major Lukan theme (Acts 10).',
        7: 'GREEK: The term παῖς (pais) here can mean "servant" or "child," and is distinct from δοῦλος (doulos, "slave") used in v.2. Luke uses both terms, reflecting the intimate relationship. The centurion\'s faith that Jesus can heal by a spoken word (λόγῳ, logō — a single word/command) parallels the creative word of God in Genesis and the Psalms (Ps 33:6, 107:20). THEOLOGICAL: This anticipates the authority of Christ\'s word over all creation.',
        9: 'THEOLOGICAL: That Jesus "marveled" (ἐθαύμασεν, ethaumasen) is remarkable — the divine Son expressing genuine amazement at human faith. This is one of only two occasions where Jesus is said to marvel (cf. Mark 6:6, at unbelief). The centurion\'s faith surpasses that found in all Israel, establishing a pattern Luke develops throughout Luke-Acts: Gentile faith shaming Israelite unfaith.',
        12: 'GREEK: μονογενής (monogenēs) — "only-begotten" or "one-of-a-kind" — the same word used of Jesus in John 3:16. TYPOLOGY: The widow\'s only son echoes the widow of Zarephath whose son Elijah raised (1 Kgs 17:17-24). Luke deliberately parallels Jesus with Elijah, yet shows Jesus as greater — Elijah prayed; Jesus commands by His own authority.',
        13: 'THEOLOGICAL: Luke calls Jesus ὁ κύριος (ho kyrios, "the Lord") in the narrative voice — not merely "teacher" or "rabbi." This is Luke\'s confession of Jesus\'s divine lordship. The verb ἐσπλαγχνίσθη (esplanchnisthē, "had compassion") derives from σπλάγχνα (splanchna, "inner organs/bowels"), signifying the deepest visceral compassion.',
        14: 'GREEK: σορός (soros) — an open bier or coffin for carrying the dead, not a sealed tomb. THEOLOGICAL: Jesus touches the bier, which would render one ceremonially unclean under Torah (Num 19:11-16), yet rather than defilement passing to Jesus, life passes from Him to the dead. His holiness is contagious rather than contaminated. His direct command "Arise" (ἐγέρθητι, egerthēti) carries the same authority as the creative word of God.',
        16: 'TYPOLOGY: The crowd\'s declaration "God has visited His people" (ἐπεσκέψατο ὁ θεὸς τὸν λαὸν αὐτοῦ) echoes Zechariah\'s prophecy in Luke 1:68 and the language of Exodus (Exod 4:31). The verb ἐπισκέπτομαι (episképtomai) carries divine council overtones — God personally intervening in the affairs of His people. THEOLOGICAL: They rightly perceive divine visitation but may not yet grasp that this prophet IS God visiting in person.',
        19: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The Coming One" (ὁ ἐρχόμενος, ho erchomenos) is a messianic title drawn from Ps 118:26, Mal 3:1, and Hab 2:3 (LXX). John\'s question from prison is not necessarily doubt but may be a pedagogical sending — ensuring his disciples encounter Jesus directly. TYPOLOGY: The question itself reflects the eschatological expectation of Second Temple Judaism for a definitive redemptive figure.',
        22: 'TYPOLOGY: Jesus\'s answer directly echoes Isaiah 35:5-6 and 61:1 — the hallmarks of the messianic age. Each item corresponds to an Isaianic prophecy: blind seeing (Isa 29:18), lame walking (Isa 35:6), lepers cleansed (implied in Isa 53:4), deaf hearing (Isa 35:5), dead raised (Isa 26:19), poor evangelized (Isa 61:1). Jesus answers not with a title but with evidence — His works fulfill the prophetic script.',
        23: 'GREEK: σκανδαλίζω (skandalizō) — "to cause to stumble, to be offended" — from σκάνδαλον (skandalon), a trap-stick or stumbling block. THEOLOGICAL: This gentle warning implies that the Messiah\'s manner of coming — humble, suffering, not immediately overthrowing Rome — could be a stumbling block. Blessedness belongs to those who do not find Jesus\'s messianic profile offensive (cf. 1 Pet 2:8, Isa 8:14).',
        27: 'TYPOLOGY: This is a composite quotation from Mal 3:1 and Exod 23:20 (LXX). In Malachi, YHWH says "I send My messenger before MY face" — yet here Jesus applies it as "before YOUR face," identifying Himself as the Lord whom the messenger precedes. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The "messenger" (ángelos) language connects John to the role of the divine herald who prepares the way for God\'s own arrival, as in the angelic messenger tradition.',
        28: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus\'s declaration about John is both the highest human commendation and a startling relativization — the least in the kingdom of God surpasses even this greatest of prophets. This indicates a radical eschatological shift: the kingdom inaugurated by Jesus creates a new order of existence that transcends even the greatest figures of the old covenant era. GREEK: μείζων (meizōn) is comparative of μέγας — "greater," used twice with deliberate contrast.',
        30: 'THEOLOGICAL: The βουλή (boulē) or "counsel/purpose" of God is a term with divine council resonance — the deliberated will and decree of God (cf. Acts 2:23, 4:28, Eph 1:11). The Pharisees and lawyers "rejected" (ἠθέτησαν, ēthetēsan) this counsel "against themselves" (εἰς ἑαυτούς) — their rejection harms only themselves, not God\'s plan. DIVINE_COUNCIL: God\'s boulē is His sovereign decree, and human rejection cannot nullify it but only exclude the rejector.',
        35: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Wisdom was justified by all her children" — σοφία (sophia) personified, likely an allusion to Proverbs 8 and the Wisdom tradition. The "children" of wisdom are those who respond rightly — both to John\'s asceticism and to Jesus\'s table fellowship. GREEK: ἐδικαιώθη (edikaiōthē) — "was justified/vindicated" — wisdom is shown to be right by the fruit of those who embrace her ways.',
        38: 'HISTORICAL: Reclining at table in Greco-Roman fashion meant lying on one\'s side with feet extended away from the table, making them accessible. A woman\'s unbound hair in public was considered scandalous in Jewish culture, heightening the scene\'s social transgression. GREEK: The imperfect tenses (κατεφίλει, ἤλειφεν) indicate continuous, repeated action — she kept kissing, kept anointing — expressing lavish, unrestrained devotion.',
        47: 'THEOLOGICAL: The logic of this verse is often misread. Jesus does not say her love earned forgiveness; rather, her great love is the evidence and result of great forgiveness already received. The parable in vv.41-42 makes the causal direction clear: forgiveness produces love, not the reverse. The one forgiven much, loves much. GREEK: ἀφέωνται (apheōntai) is perfect passive — "have been and remain forgiven" — the state is already accomplished.',
        49: 'THEOLOGICAL: The question "Who is this who even forgives sins?" echoes the controversy in Luke 5:21 where scribes and Pharisees asked the same. In Jewish theology, only God forgives sins (Isa 43:25, Ps 51:4). Jesus\'s act of forgiving sins is an implicit claim to divine authority and identity — precisely the conclusion Luke intends his readers to reach. DIVINE_COUNCIL: Forgiveness of sins is a prerogative of the divine throne; Jesus exercises it from a dining couch.',
        50: 'GREEK: σέσωκέν (sesōken) — perfect active of σῴζω (sōzō), meaning "has saved" with lasting result. The word encompasses physical healing, spiritual deliverance, and eschatological salvation. THEOLOGICAL: "Go into peace" (εἰς εἰρήνην, eis eirēnēn) — not merely "in peace" (ἐν εἰρήνῃ) but "into peace" — she enters a new state of shalom, of wholeness and right relationship with God. Faith is the instrument, not the cause; Christ is the source of salvation.',
    },
    8: {
        1: 'GREEK: The phrase "ἐν τῷ καθεξῆς" (en tō kathexēs) is a distinctly Lukan expression meaning "in the time following" or "in succession," emphasizing the orderly progression of Jesus\'s ministry. "Εὐαγγελιζόμενος" (euangelizomenos, Strong\'s G2097) means "bringing good news" — a present middle participle indicating ongoing proclamation. HISTORICAL: This itinerant preaching circuit through both cities (poleis) and villages (kōmas) reflects the comprehensive nature of Jesus\'s Galilean ministry.',
        2: 'GREEK: "Τεθεραπευμέναι" (tetherapeumenai) is a perfect passive participle, indicating a completed healing with lasting effect. HISTORICAL: Mary Magdalene\'s seven demons (ἑπτὰ δαιμόνια) indicate a severe case of spiritual oppression; the number seven in Jewish thought signifies completeness. She is distinguished from the sinful woman of Luke 7:36-50, despite later conflation in Western tradition.',
        3: 'HISTORICAL: Joanna\'s connection to Chuza (Χουζᾶ), Herod Antipas\'s steward (ἐπίτροπος, epitropos — a high-ranking household administrator), reveals that the gospel had penetrated even Herod\'s court. "Διηκόνουν" (diēkonoun) indicates ongoing financial and material support — these women were patrons of the movement, a remarkable feature in first-century Judaism.',
        10: 'GREEK: "Μυστήρια" (mystēria, Strong\'s G3466) does not mean hidden esoteric knowledge but rather divine truths previously concealed and now revealed to those with ears to hear. TYPOLOGY: The quotation draws on Isaiah 6:9-10 (LXX), where the prophet\'s commission includes the hardening of Israel — a pattern now fulfilled in Jesus\'s parabolic teaching, where the same word brings illumination to disciples and obscurity to the resistant. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The mysteries of the kingdom relate to God\'s sovereign plan now being unveiled through the Messiah.',
        12: 'THEOLOGICAL: Luke alone among the Synoptics names "the devil" (ὁ διάβολος, ho diabolos, Strong\'s G1228) rather than "Satan" in the sower interpretation, emphasizing the role of the cosmic adversary in preventing saving faith. The purpose clause "ἵνα μὴ πιστεύσαντες σωθῶσιν" (that they might not, having believed, be saved) makes explicit the soteriological stakes: the devil\'s aim is to prevent the faith-to-salvation sequence.',
        15: 'GREEK: "Καρδίᾳ καλῇ καὶ ἀγαθῇ" (kardia kalē kai agathē) — "noble and good heart" — uses language resonant with Hellenistic moral philosophy (the καλὸς κἀγαθός ideal), yet Luke applies it to receptivity to God\'s word. "Κατέχουσιν" (katechousin, Strong\'s G2722) means to "hold fast" or "retain," implying active grip against opposing forces. "Ὑπομονῇ" (hypomonē) denotes patient, steadfast endurance under trial — the distinguishing mark of true faith.',
        17: 'THEOLOGICAL: The pairing of "κρυπτόν" (hidden) and "ἀπόκρυφον" (secret/concealed, Strong\'s G614) emphasizes that all things hidden in the present age will be brought to manifest disclosure. This applies both to the present hiddenness of the kingdom and to the future eschatological revelation when all will be laid bare.',
        21: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus redefines kinship around obedience to the word of God rather than biological descent. This is not a rejection of Mary but a radical declaration that spiritual family, constituted by hearing and doing God\'s word, takes precedence. TYPOLOGY: This echoes the Deuteronomic call to covenant faithfulness (Deut 6:4-6) and anticipates the new covenant community formed around Christ.',
        24: 'GREEK: "Ἐπιστάτα" (epistata, Strong\'s G1988) is a uniquely Lukan title for Jesus, used only by his disciples, meaning "Master" or "Commander" — carrying overtones of authority. THEOLOGICAL: Jesus rebukes (ἐπετίμησεν, epetimēsen) the wind and the raging water with the same verb used for rebuking demons (4:35), suggesting sovereign authority over both spiritual powers and the natural order. TYPOLOGY: This echoes Psalm 107:29 and Psalm 89:9, where God alone stills the seas — the disciples\' question "Who then is this?" points toward divine identity.',
        25: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: The question "Who then is this?" (Τίς ἄρα οὗτός ἐστιν) is theologically loaded. In the Old Testament, sovereignty over sea and storm is exclusively the prerogative of YHWH (Ps 65:7; 89:9; 107:29; Job 38:8-11). The disciples are confronting the implication that Jesus exercises divine authority over creation itself.',
        28: 'GREEK: "Τί ἐμοὶ καὶ σοί" (ti emoi kai soi) is a Semitic idiom meaning "What have I to do with you?" — expressing awareness of a fundamental incompatibility between the demonic realm and the Son of God. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The demon\'s identification of Jesus as "Son of God Most High" (υἱὲ τοῦ θεοῦ τοῦ ὑψίστου) uses "Most High" (Hypsistos, Strong\'s G5310), a title emphasizing God\'s supreme sovereignty over all spiritual beings. The demons recognize the divine council hierarchy that humans fail to perceive.',
        31: 'GREEK: "Ἄβυσσον" (abysson, Strong\'s G12) refers to the abyss or bottomless deep — the place of confinement for rebellious spiritual entities. DIVINE_COUNCIL: This detail is unique to Luke and reveals the demons\' awareness of their appointed eschatological judgment. The abyss appears in Jewish apocalyptic literature (1 Enoch 10:4-6; Jubilees 5:6) as the prison of fallen spiritual beings, and in Revelation 9:1-11 and 20:1-3 as the place of binding. The demons beg not to be sent there before the appointed time.',
        39: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus commands the healed man to declare what "God" (ὁ θεός) has done, but the man proclaims what "Jesus" (ὁ Ἰησοῦς) has done — Luke subtly identifies the work of Jesus with the work of God. This is one of the few cases where Jesus commissions proclamation rather than commanding silence, notably in Gentile/semi-pagan territory (the Decapolis region).',
        42: 'GREEK: "Μονογενής" (monogenēs, Strong\'s G3439) means "only-begotten" or "one of a kind" — the same term applied to Jesus in John 3:16. Luke uses it to heighten the pathos: she is the sole daughter, irreplaceable. STRUCTURE: Luke masterfully interweaves the Jairus narrative with the hemorrhaging woman, creating a literary sandwich (intercalation) where the themes of twelve years, faith, and being "saved/healed" (sōzō) link both stories.',
        44: 'GREEK: "Κρασπέδου" (kraspedou, Strong\'s G2899) refers to the tassel or fringe of the garment, the ritual tzitzit commanded in Numbers 15:38-39 and Deuteronomy 22:12. TYPOLOGY: The woman\'s touch of the garment fringe recalls Malachi 4:2 (LXX 3:20), where healing is found "in the wings" of the Sun of Righteousness — "wings" (kanaph) being the same Hebrew term for the corner of a garment bearing the fringes.',
        46: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Δύναμιν ἐξεληλυθυῖαν ἀπ\' ἐμοῦ" (dynamin exelēlythuian ap\' emou) — "power having gone out from me." This is not magical force drained involuntarily; Jesus perceives it because he is the conscious source and mediator of divine power. His question is pedagogical, drawing the woman from secrecy to public confession of faith.',
        48: 'GREEK: "Σέσωκέν" (sesōken) is the perfect tense of sōzō (Strong\'s G4982), meaning both "has saved" and "has healed" — the double meaning is theologically intentional. Physical healing is the sign of comprehensive salvation. "Εἰς εἰρήνην" (eis eirēnēn) echoes the Hebrew shalom — she is dismissed not merely without disease but into wholeness and covenant peace.',
        50: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Μόνον πίστευσον" (monon pisteuson) — "only believe" — is an aorist imperative calling for decisive, immediate faith in the face of death\'s apparent finality. The promise "σωθήσεται" (sōthēsetai, "she shall be saved/healed") again holds the double meaning of sōzō, encompassing both physical restoration and eschatological salvation. Jesus calls Jairus to the same faith that saved the hemorrhaging woman.',
        54: 'GREEK: "Ἡ παῖς, ἔγειρε" (hē pais, egeire) — "Child, arise!" — uses the present imperative of egeirō (Strong\'s G1453), the same root used throughout the NT for resurrection. TYPOLOGY: Jesus takes her by the hand (kratēsas tēs cheiros), an act that would render one ritually unclean by contact with a corpse under Levitical law (Num 19:11), yet instead of defilement flowing to Jesus, life flows from him — a reversal pattern seen also with the leper (Luke 5:13) and the hemorrhaging woman.',
        55: 'GREEK: "Ἐπέστρεψεν τὸ πνεῦμα αὐτῆς" (epestrepsen to pneuma autēs) — "her spirit returned." This reflects the Jewish anthropology where death involves the departure of the spirit (ruach/pneuma) from the body (cf. Eccl 12:7; Gen 35:18). The command to give her food demonstrates the physical, bodily reality of the restoration — this is no ghostly apparition but genuine resurrection to embodied life.',
    },
    9: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Synkalesamenos" (συγκαλεσάμενος) is a middle participle meaning "having called together" — indicating Jesus personally assembled the Twelve. "Dynamis" (δύναμις, Strong\'s G1411) denotes inherent power or ability, while "exousia" (ἐξουσία, G1849) denotes delegated authority. Jesus grants both the raw spiritual power and the right to wield it. THEOLOGICAL: This dual commission of power and authority reflects Christ\'s own divine prerogatives being delegated to his appointed representatives.',
        2: 'THEOLOGICAL: The twin mission — proclaiming the kingdom of God and healing — mirrors Jesus\' own ministry pattern (Luke 4:43; 6:18). The kingdom (basileía, G932) is not merely announced but demonstrated through the signs accompanying it. TYPOLOGY: The sending of the Twelve echoes God sending Moses and the seventy elders (Num 11:16-17), now reconstituted around the Messiah.',
        5: 'HISTORICAL: Shaking dust from the feet was a Jewish symbolic act performed when leaving Gentile territory, signifying separation from defilement. Jesus instructs the Twelve to treat rejecting Jewish towns as though they were pagan — a severe prophetic sign. The phrase "eis martyrion" (εἰς μαρτύριον) indicates this act serves as a legal witness against them at judgment.',
        16: 'TYPOLOGY: Jesus\' actions — taking, looking up to heaven, blessing, breaking, and giving — form a eucharistic pattern that reappears at the Last Supper (Luke 22:19). The feeding in the wilderness also typologically echoes God\'s provision of manna through Moses (Exod 16). THEOLOGICAL: Christ acts here as both the new Moses providing bread and as the true source of the bread, foreshadowing the Lord\'s Supper.',
        17: 'GREEK: "Klasmaton kophinoi dodeka" (κλασμάτων κόφινοι δώδεκα) — twelve baskets of broken pieces. The "kophinos" (G2894) was a distinctly Jewish wicker basket. THEOLOGICAL: The twelve baskets correspond to the twelve tribes of Israel, signifying that the Messiah\'s provision is abundant and sufficient for all of God\'s people. The superabundance points to eschatological fullness.',
        20: 'THEOLOGICAL: Peter\'s confession "Ton Christon tou Theou" (Τὸν Χριστὸν τοῦ Θεοῦ) — "The Christ of God" — is the Lukan form of the great confession (cf. Matt 16:16; Mark 8:29). "Christos" (G5547) translates Hebrew "Mashiach" — the Anointed One, the promised Davidic King. The genitive "tou Theou" marks Jesus as God\'s own Anointed, the one set apart and commissioned by God himself for the eschatological rule.',
        22: 'GREEK: "Dei" (δεῖ, G1163) expresses divine necessity — "it is necessary" according to the determined plan of God. This is not mere fate but the fulfillment of prophetic Scripture. TYPOLOGY: The suffering, rejection, and rising of the Son of Man fulfills the pattern of the Suffering Servant (Isa 53) and the righteous sufferer of the Psalms (Ps 22; 118:22). The "third day" echoes Hosea 6:2.',
        23: 'GREEK: "Arnatō heauton" (ἀρνησάσθω ἑαυτόν) — "let him deny himself" — is an aorist imperative indicating a decisive, complete act. "Kath\' hēmeran" (καθ\' ἡμέραν) — "daily" — is unique to Luke\'s account, emphasizing the continuous, repeated nature of cross-bearing discipleship. THEOLOGICAL: The call to take up one\'s cross was shocking — the cross was Rome\'s instrument of shameful execution. Jesus redefines messianic discipleship not as triumphalist power but as self-renouncing suffering.',
        26: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: Jesus speaks of coming "in his glory and the glory of the Father and of the holy angels" (ἐν τῇ δόξῃ αὐτοῦ καὶ τοῦ πατρὸς καὶ τῶν ἁγίων ἀγγέλων). This is a divine council scene: the Son of Man arrives as cosmic judge amid the heavenly host. The imagery draws on Daniel 7:13-14 where the Son of Man approaches the Ancient of Days and receives dominion, accompanied by the angelic myriads. Jesus claims participation in the Father\'s own glory — a claim to divine identity.',
        31: 'GREEK: "Exodon" (ἔξοδον, G1841) — "exodus" or "departure" — is a deeply loaded term. Luke deliberately uses this word rather than "thanaton" (death). TYPOLOGY: Moses and Elijah discuss Jesus\' "exodus" which he is about to "fulfill" (plēroun) in Jerusalem. This connects Jesus\' death, resurrection, and ascension to the original Exodus — the great redemptive act of God delivering his people. Jesus accomplishes the new and greater Exodus, liberating humanity from the bondage of sin and death. Moses represents the Law, Elijah the Prophets — both witness to Christ.',
        35: 'THEOLOGICAL: The divine voice from the cloud echoes the baptism (Luke 3:22) but adds "ho eklelegmenos" (ὁ ἐκλελεγμένος) — "the Chosen One" — a title drawing on Isaiah 42:1 (LXX). This identifies Jesus as the Servant of the Lord. The command "autou akouete" (αὐτοῦ ἀκούετε) — "hear him!" — echoes Deuteronomy 18:15, the promise of the Prophet like Moses. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The cloud (nephélē) represents the divine presence, the same glory-cloud (Shekinah) that filled the tabernacle and temple (Exod 40:34-35; 1 Kgs 8:10-11). God himself speaks from within it, identifying Jesus as his unique Son.',
        44: 'GREEK: "Thesthe hymeis eis ta ōta hymōn" (Θέσθε ὑμεῖς εἰς τὰ ὦτα ὑμῶν) — literally "Put you into your ears" — is an emphatic Semitic idiom meaning "let these words sink deeply in." The pronoun "hymeis" is emphatic, stressing the disciples specifically. THEOLOGICAL: Jesus issues this solemn charge amid the crowd\'s amazement at his power, sharply contrasting divine majesty with the coming betrayal — "paradidosthai" (παραδίδοσθαι, G3860), to be handed over, a term with both judicial and covenantal treachery connotations.',
        51: 'GREEK: "Analēmpseōs" (ἀναλήμψεως, G354) — a hapax legomenon in the NT — refers to Jesus\' "being taken up," denoting his ascension. STRUCTURE: This verse marks the pivotal turning point of Luke\'s Gospel — the beginning of the great "Travel Narrative" or "Journey to Jerusalem" (9:51–19:44). Jesus "set his face" (to prosōpon estērisen) recalls Isaiah 50:7 (LXX), the Servant\'s resolve in suffering. THEOLOGICAL: The entire complex of suffering, death, resurrection, and ascension is encompassed in this single word "analēmpsis," showing Luke views these as one unified redemptive event.',
        54: 'TYPOLOGY: James and John allude to Elijah calling fire from heaven upon the soldiers of Ahaziah (2 Kgs 1:10-12). The disciples misunderstand the nature of Jesus\' messianic mission — his journey to Jerusalem is not one of fiery judgment upon rejecting peoples but of self-sacrifice. HISTORICAL: Samaritan-Jewish hostility was longstanding (cf. Ezra 4; John 4:9). The Samaritans\' refusal was rooted in the religious rivalry over the proper place of worship — Jerusalem versus Mount Gerizim.',
        58: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The Son of Man has nowhere to lay his head" reveals the radical homelessness of the incarnate King. TYPOLOGY: The foxes have dens and the birds have nests — even the creatures of the earth have dwelling places, yet the one through whom all things were made (John 1:3) has no earthly home. This inverts all expectations of messianic grandeur and royal comfort.',
        62: 'GREEK: "Arotron" (ἄροτρον, G723) — "plough" — appears only here in the NT. The image of ploughing requires looking forward to cut straight furrows; looking back produces crooked, useless work. THEOLOGICAL: Jesus demands undivided commitment to the kingdom of God. The saying echoes Elijah\'s call of Elisha (1 Kgs 19:19-21), where Elisha was permitted to say farewell — yet Jesus demands even greater urgency. The kingdom of God surpasses all prior prophetic calls in its radical demand for wholehearted allegiance.',
    },
    10: {
        1: 'GREEK: ἀνέδειξεν (anedeixen, from anadeiknymi) means "appointed" or "publicly designated" — a formal commissioning. The number seventy-two (variant: seventy) likely echoes the seventy elders of Israel (Num 11:16-25) and the seventy nations of Genesis 10 in the LXX tradition. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The seventy nations tradition from the Table of Nations (Gen 10; Deut 32:8-9 LXX) assigns seventy(-two) nations to the sons of God; the sending of seventy(-two) missionaries may symbolize the gospel\'s reach to all nations under the authority of the true Lord.',
        2: 'GREEK: θερισμός (therismos, "harvest") carries eschatological weight, pointing to the final ingathering of God\'s people. ἐκβάλῃ (ekbalē, from ekballō) is strikingly forceful — literally "cast out" or "thrust out" — suggesting urgency and divine initiative in sending workers. TYPOLOGY: The harvest imagery echoes Joel 3:13 and anticipates the eschatological gathering under the Messiah\'s reign.',
        3: 'GREEK: ἄρνας (arnas, "lambs") is used only here in the NT in this sending context (Matthew 10:16 uses πρόβατα, "sheep"). The image is deliberately more vulnerable than sheep — these are lambs among wolves, emphasizing total dependence on the Sender. THEOLOGICAL: The Messiah sends his emissaries into hostile territory not with worldly power but under divine protection.',
        6: 'GREEK: υἱὸς εἰρήνης (huios eirēnēs, "son of peace") is a Semitic idiom meaning one characterized by or destined for peace — one receptive to the shalom of God\'s kingdom. ἐπαναπαήσεται (epanapaēsetai, "shall rest upon") echoes the Spirit resting upon persons in the OT (Num 11:25-26; Isa 11:2).',
        12: 'THEOLOGICAL: The pronouncement that Sodom\'s judgment will be more tolerable than that of cities rejecting the seventy-two implies a graduated judgment based on revelation received. Those who reject the direct heralds of the Messiah bear greater culpability than Sodom, which never witnessed such works. TYPOLOGY: This escalation pattern echoes Ezekiel 16:48-50 where Sodom is used as a comparative standard of judgment.',
        15: 'GREEK: The language echoes Isaiah 14:13-15 (LXX), the taunt against the king of Babylon who sought to ascend to heaven but was brought down to Sheol/Hades. TYPOLOGY: Capernaum, exalted by the presence and ministry of the Messiah, faces the severest judgment for its rejection — mirroring the cosmic pride-and-fall pattern of Isaiah 14. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The Isaiah 14 background invokes the divine council setting where the arrogant one who would place his throne among the stars of God is cast down.',
        16: 'THEOLOGICAL: This verse establishes an unbroken chain of delegated authority: to reject the seventy-two is to reject Christ, and to reject Christ is to reject the Father who sent him. This reflects the šāliaḥ ("sent one") principle in Jewish law — an agent bears the full authority of the one who sends him. The Messiah here claims unique agency from the Father, extending it through his appointed emissaries.',
        18: 'GREEK: ἐθεώρουν (etheōroun, imperfect tense of theōreō) — "I was beholding" — suggests a visionary or continuous observation, not a single past event. DIVINE_COUNCIL: Satan\'s fall "as lightning from heaven" resonates with the divine council motif of rebellious heavenly beings being cast down (Isa 14:12; Ezek 28:16-17; Rev 12:7-9). The exorcisms performed by the seventy-two are earthly manifestations of a heavenly defeat already in progress through Christ\'s authority.',
        19: 'TYPOLOGY: The authority to tread upon serpents and scorpions echoes Genesis 3:15 (the protoevangelium — the seed of the woman crushing the serpent\'s head) and Psalm 91:13. The "power of the enemy" (τὴν δύναμιν τοῦ ἐχθροῦ) identifies Satan and his hosts as the ultimate adversary. THEOLOGICAL: Christ grants to his emissaries participation in his own messianic victory over the hostile spiritual powers.',
        20: 'GREEK: ἐγγέγραπται (engegraptai, perfect passive of engraphō) — "have been written and remain written" — the perfect tense emphasizes the permanent, completed nature of the heavenly inscription. THEOLOGICAL: Rejoicing should be rooted not in spiritual power exercised but in one\'s secure standing before God — names inscribed in the heavenly register (cf. Exod 32:32; Dan 12:1; Phil 4:3; Rev 20:12).',
        21: 'GREEK: ἠγαλλιάσατο (ēgalliasato, from agalliaō) — "exulted" or "rejoiced greatly" — a rare description of Jesus\'s emotion, used in the LXX for ecstatic praise (Ps 16:9). THEOLOGICAL: Jesus\'s prayer reveals the Father\'s sovereign election: divine mysteries are hidden from the humanly wise (σοφῶν καὶ συνετῶν) and revealed to νηπίοις ("infants," the unlearned and dependent). This is a Johannine-sounding passage within the Synoptic tradition, affirming the Father-Son relationship of mutual exclusive knowledge.',
        22: 'THEOLOGICAL: This verse presents the most exalted Christological claim in the Synoptic Gospels. The mutual exclusive knowledge between Father and Son (cf. John 10:15; Matt 11:27) places the Son in a unique ontological relationship with the Father — no creature fully knows God except through the Son\'s sovereign revelation. The Son possesses the divine prerogative of revelation (ἀποκαλύψαι). DIVINE_COUNCIL: Unlike any angelic being in the divine council, the Son alone possesses exhaustive knowledge of the Father, establishing his supreme status above all heavenly beings.',
        27: 'GREEK: The lawyer quotes Deuteronomy 6:5 (the Shema) combined with Leviticus 19:18. The fourfold division — καρδίας (heart), ψυχῇ (soul), ἰσχύϊ (strength), διανοίᾳ (mind) — expands the Hebrew original\'s threefold formula, representing the totality of human devotion. THEOLOGICAL: The entire Law is summarized in vertical love toward God and horizontal love toward neighbor — the two tablets of the covenant (cf. Rom 13:8-10).',
        30: 'HISTORICAL: The road from Jerusalem to Jericho descended approximately 3,400 feet over 17 miles through the Judean wilderness — notoriously dangerous terrain called the "Ascent of Blood" (Adummim) due to frequent robberies. GREEK: ἡμιθανῆ (hēmithanē) — "half-dead" — is a NT hapax legomenon, emphasizing the extreme severity of the assault.',
        33: 'HISTORICAL: Samaritans were despised by Jews as ethnically mixed and religiously heretical (cf. 2 Kings 17:24-41; John 4:9). Jesus\'s choice of a Samaritan as the hero would have been shocking and deeply offensive to his Jewish audience. GREEK: ἐσπλαγχνίσθη (esplanchnisthē, from splanchnizomai) — "was moved in his inward parts" — denotes the deepest visceral compassion, used in the Gospels almost exclusively of Jesus or characters representing divine mercy.',
        37: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus inverts the lawyer\'s question. The lawyer asked "Who is my neighbor?" seeking to limit the obligation. Jesus asks "Who became a neighbor?" — transforming the question from one of boundary-drawing to one of active mercy. The command "Go and do likewise" makes neighbor-love an unbounded, self-giving action rather than a category to be defined. TYPOLOGY: Some patristic interpreters saw the Good Samaritan as a figure of Christ himself — the rejected one who alone shows mercy to fallen humanity, binds wounds, and promises to return.',
        42: 'GREEK: The textual tradition varies between "few things are needful, or one" (ὀλίγων δέ ἐστιν χρεία ἢ ἑνός) and simpler readings. The "one thing needful" (ἑνός) points to the singular priority of attending to Christ\'s word. μερίδα (merida, "portion") carries covenantal overtones — one\'s allotted inheritance (cf. Ps 16:5; 73:26). THEOLOGICAL: Mary\'s posture at the Lord\'s feet — the posture of a disciple — is declared the "good portion" that cannot be taken away, establishing the primacy of receiving Christ\'s word over even legitimate service.',
    },
    11: {
        1: 'GREEK: The construction Καὶ ἐγένετο ἐν τῷ εἶναι αὐτόν (kaì egéneto en tō̧ eînai autón) is a Septuagintal Hebraism reflecting the Hebrew wayĕhî construction, common in Luke\'s narrative style. The verb προσεύχομαι (proseúchomai, Strong\'s G4336) indicates earnest, devoted prayer. HISTORICAL: Luke uniquely records that a disciple\'s request prompted the Lord\'s Prayer, whereas Matthew places it within the Sermon on the Mount (Matt 6:9-13). John the Baptist evidently had a distinctive prayer tradition for his disciples.',
        2: 'THEOLOGICAL: Luke\'s version of the Lord\'s Prayer is shorter than Matthew\'s (Matt 6:9-13), omitting "who art in heaven," "thy will be done," and the doxology. The aorist imperative ἁγιασθήτω (hagiasthḗtō) is a divine passive — God himself is asked to cause his name to be hallowed. The petition for the kingdom\'s coming reflects the eschatological hope central to Jesus\'s proclamation. TYPOLOGY: The address "Father" (Πάτερ) without further qualification reflects the intimate divine-filial relationship Jesus models, distinct from typical Jewish liturgical address.',
        3: 'GREEK: The word ἐπιούσιον (epioúsion, Strong\'s G1967) is one of the most debated terms in the NT, a near-hapax legomenon found only here and in Matt 6:11. Its etymology is uncertain — possibly from ἐπί + οὐσία ("for subsistence/existence"), from ἐπί + ἰέναι ("for the coming day"), or from ἐπί + εἶναι ("sufficient for being"). Origen noted it was not found in ordinary Greek usage. The present imperative δίδου (dídou) suggests continuous, daily giving.',
        4: 'THEOLOGICAL: Luke uses ἁμαρτίας (hamartías, "sins") where Matthew has ὀφειλήματα ("debts," Matt 6:12), though Luke retains the debt metaphor with ὀφείλοντι (opheílonti, "everyone indebted to us"). The petition against πειρασμός (peirasmós, Strong\'s G3986) may denote either "temptation" or "testing/trial," with overtones of the eschatological trial. TYPOLOGY: The forgiveness petition echoes the Day of Atonement pattern — divine forgiveness enabling communal reconciliation (Lev 16).',
        8: 'GREEK: The key term ἀναίδειαν (anaídeian, Strong\'s G335) is a hapax legomenon in the NT, meaning "shamelessness" or "shameless persistence." Some scholars render it "avoidance of shame" (i.e., the sleeper gives in to avoid the shame of refusing hospitality). HISTORICAL: In the honor-shame culture of first-century Palestine, refusing hospitality — especially to a traveler — brought communal disgrace. The parable argues from lesser to greater: if even a reluctant human responds to persistent asking, how much more God.',
        13: 'THEOLOGICAL: This is a critically significant Lukan variation from Matthew\'s parallel (Matt 7:11), where Matthew has "good things" (ἀγαθά) but Luke specifies πνεῦμα ἅγιον (pneûma hágion, "Holy Spirit"). This reflects Luke\'s distinctive pneumatology — the Holy Spirit as the supreme gift of the Father. The argument moves from lesser to greater (qal wahomer): if evil humans give good gifts, how much more the heavenly Father gives the Spirit. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The Father "who is from heaven" (ὁ ἐξ οὐρανοῦ) locates God in his heavenly council seat as the supreme giver.',
        15: 'HISTORICAL: Βεελζεβούλ (Beelzeboúl, Strong\'s G954) derives from the Philistine deity Baal-Zebub ("Lord of the Flies," 2 Kgs 1:2), reinterpreted in Second Temple Judaism as a title for Satan or the chief of demons. The accusation implies Jesus operates under demonic authority rather than divine. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The charge reflects an understanding of a hierarchical realm of hostile spiritual powers — a "ruler" (ἄρχοντι) presiding over lesser demons — which Jesus does not deny as a cosmological structure but refutes as applied to himself.',
        20: 'THEOLOGICAL: The phrase "finger of God" (δακτύλῳ θεοῦ) is a direct allusion to Exod 8:19 (LXX 8:15), where Pharaoh\'s magicians recognize God\'s power in Moses\'s signs. Matthew\'s parallel (Matt 12:28) has "Spirit of God," suggesting Luke preserves the more archaic Exodus typology. The verb ἔφθασεν (éphthasen, "has come upon") is aorist, indicating the kingdom\'s arrival is not merely future but has already broken in through Jesus\'s exorcisms. TYPOLOGY: Jesus\'s exorcisms recapitulate the Exodus liberation — as God\'s finger defeated Egypt\'s powers, so now it defeats demonic powers. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The "finger of God" implies direct divine-council authority exercised through Jesus, bypassing any intermediary spiritual hierarchy.',
        22: 'THEOLOGICAL: The "stronger one" (ἰσχυρότερος) who overcomes the "strong man" (ἰσχυρός) is Christ himself overcoming Satan. The term πανοπλίαν (panoplían, Strong\'s G3833, "full armor") is used elsewhere only in Eph 6:11,13 for the believer\'s spiritual armor. Jesus strips Satan of his defensive and offensive capacity. DIVINE_COUNCIL: This passage presents a cosmic conflict theology — two rival powers contending, with Christ as the divinely authorized warrior who plunders the enemy\'s domain (cf. Isa 49:24-25, Isa 53:12).',
        28: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus redirects honor from biological motherhood to obedient hearing and keeping (φυλάσσοντες, phylássontes, Strong\'s G5442) of God\'s word. This is not a rejection of Mary but a reorientation of blessedness toward covenant faithfulness. The term μενοῦν (menoûn) is an emphatic particle meaning "rather" or "on the contrary indeed," making this a strong correction. TYPOLOGY: This echoes the Deuteronomic pattern where blessing follows obedience to the divine word (Deut 28:1-2).',
        30: 'TYPOLOGY: Jonah\'s three days in the great fish prefigure Christ\'s death and resurrection (Matt 12:40 makes this explicit). But Luke\'s emphasis is on Jonah as a sign-figure to the Ninevites — as Jonah himself, having emerged from apparent death, was a sign calling Nineveh to repentance, so the Son of Man in his person and proclamation is a sign to this generation. The "Son of Man" title here carries both Danielic authority (Dan 7:13-14) and the suffering-servant overtone.',
        31: 'HISTORICAL: The "queen of the south" is the Queen of Sheba (1 Kgs 10:1-13; 2 Chr 9:1-12), who traveled from the Arabian Peninsula to hear Solomon\'s wisdom. THEOLOGICAL: The neuter πλεῖον (pleîon, "something greater") rather than masculine suggests Jesus points not merely to himself as greater than Solomon but to the entire reality of the kingdom breaking in — the wisdom, power, and presence of God manifested in his ministry surpasses all prior revelations.',
        34: 'GREEK: The term ἁπλοῦς (haploûs, Strong\'s G573) means "single, simple, sound, healthy" — denoting undivided focus or generosity (the opposite of a "double" or "evil" eye). In Jewish idiom, the "good eye" signifies generosity and the "evil eye" (πονηρός, ponērós) signifies stinginess or moral corruption. THEOLOGICAL: The eye as lamp of the body serves as a metaphor for spiritual perception — one\'s capacity to receive divine light depends on the moral condition of one\'s inner orientation.',
        41: 'GREEK: The phrase τὰ ἐνόντα (tà enónta, "the things within") is ambiguous — it could mean "give the contents [of the cup and dish] as alms" or "give from your inner disposition." THEOLOGICAL: Jesus redirects from external ritual purity to inward transformation expressed in concrete mercy (ἐλεημοσύνη, eleēmosýnē, "alms/mercy"). True cleanliness comes not from ceremonial washing but from generous hearts that reflect God\'s own character.',
        49: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The Wisdom of God said" (ἡ σοφία τοῦ θεοῦ εἶπεν) is a striking formula with no exact OT parallel. It may refer to a lost Jewish wisdom text, to God speaking in his wisdom, or — most significantly — to Jesus identifying himself as the personified Wisdom of God (cf. Prov 8; 1 Cor 1:24,30). DIVINE_COUNCIL: The sending of prophets and apostles reflects divine council commissioning language — God dispatches his authorized messengers into the human realm, and their rejection constitutes rebellion against the heavenly court itself.',
        50: 'THEOLOGICAL: The phrase ἀπὸ καταβολῆς κόσμου (apò katabolȩ̄s kósmou, "from the foundation of the world") encompasses the entire scope of salvation history. The blood of the prophets functions as a covenant-lawsuit witness against the generation that completes the pattern of rejection. TYPOLOGY: Abel (Gen 4:8-10) represents the first righteous martyr and Zechariah (2 Chr 24:20-22) the last in the Hebrew canonical order, thus spanning the entire OT witness. The "requiring" of blood echoes Gen 9:5 where God demands an accounting for shed blood.',
        52: 'GREEK: The term κλεῖδα (kleîda, Strong\'s G2807) means "key" — the instrument of access. The "key of knowledge" (τὴν κλεῖδα τῆς γνώσεως) signifies authoritative access to understanding God\'s revelation. THEOLOGICAL: The lawyers, entrusted with interpreting Torah, have not only failed to enter the kingdom themselves but have actively blocked others from entering through their distorted teachings. This parallels Jesus\'s words to Peter about the "keys of the kingdom" (Matt 16:19) — true spiritual authority opens rather than closes access to God.',
    },
    12: {
        1: 'GREEK: ἐπισυναχθεισῶν (episynachtheisōn) — a genitive absolute from ἐπισυνάγω (Strong\'s G1996), meaning "to gather together upon," implying an overwhelming convergence. The μυριάδων (myriadōn) literally means "ten-thousands," indicating a crowd of enormous, perhaps innumerable, size. THEOLOGICAL: The leaven (ζύμη, zymē) metaphor connects to the Passover command to purge leaven (Exod 12:15), here reinterpreted as hypocrisy (ὑπόκρισις, hypokrisis, originally a theatrical term for playing a role on stage).',
        5: 'GREEK: γέενναν (geennan, Strong\'s G1067) derives from Hebrew גֵּי הִנֹּם (Ge-Hinnom), the Valley of Hinnom south of Jerusalem, associated with child sacrifice to Molech (2 Kgs 23:10; Jer 7:31) and later Jewish eschatological imagery of final judgment. THEOLOGICAL: Jesus distinguishes between those who can merely kill the body and the One (God) who possesses ἐξουσίαν (exousian, "authority") over eternal destiny. This is a definitive statement of God\'s sovereign authority over both temporal and eternal judgment.',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: The phrase "confess in me" (ὁμολογήσῃ ἐν ἐμοί) uses ἐν + dative rather than a simple accusative, suggesting not merely acknowledging Jesus but identifying with him, being "in" union with him before men. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The confession occurs "before the angels of God" (ἔμπροσθεν τῶν ἀγγέλων τοῦ θεοῦ), indicating a heavenly courtroom scene where the Son of Man serves as advocate or witness before the divine assembly (cf. Dan 7:13-14; Job 1:6; Ps 82:1).',
        10: 'THEOLOGICAL: This verse distinguishes blasphemy against the Son of Man (which is forgivable) from blasphemy against the Holy Spirit (τὸ ἅγιον πνεῦμα), which is not. The unforgivable nature points to a persistent, willful rejection of the Spirit\'s testimony concerning Christ, not a single utterance. This parallels Matt 12:31-32 and Mark 3:28-29. GREEK: βλασφημήσαντι (blasphēmēsanti) is an aorist participle, but the theological context indicates a settled disposition rather than a momentary act.',
        20: 'THEOLOGICAL: God\'s direct speech to the rich man — ἄφρων (aphrōn, "fool," Strong\'s G878) — echoes the LXX of Psalm 13:1 (MT 14:1): "The fool said in his heart, there is no God." The demand of the soul (ψυχήν σου ἀπαιτοῦσιν) uses the third person plural, possibly an impersonal construction or suggesting angelic agents of death. TYPOLOGY: The parable reverses the Deuteronomic blessing theology (Deut 28:1-14) by showing that material abundance without orientation toward God is the ultimate folly.',
        32: 'GREEK: μικρὸν ποίμνιον (mikron poimnion) — "little flock" — is a diminutive, tenderly depicting the disciples as a small, vulnerable group. THEOLOGICAL: εὐδόκησεν (eudokēsen, "was well pleased," aorist tense) indicates that the Father\'s decision to give the kingdom was a resolved, completed act of sovereign good pleasure. The kingdom is a gift (δοῦναι, dounai), not an achievement. TYPOLOGY: The shepherd-flock imagery echoes Ezek 34:11-16, where God himself becomes the shepherd of his scattered flock, a role now mediated through Jesus (cf. John 10:11-16).',
        35: 'HISTORICAL: "Loins girded" (ὀσφύες περιεζωσμέναι) recalls the Passover night command (Exod 12:11), where Israel was to eat with loins girded, ready for immediate departure. Burning lamps indicate vigilant readiness in the night watches. TYPOLOGY: The posture of readiness connects the disciples to Israel\'s exodus — they are a new exodus community awaiting the return of their Lord.',
        37: 'THEOLOGICAL: The stunning reversal in which the lord girds himself (περιζώσεται) and serves (διακονήσει) his servants at table is without parallel in ancient master-slave relationships. This foreshadows Jesus washing the disciples\' feet (John 13:4-5) and his declaration that he came "not to be served but to serve" (Mark 10:45). GREEK: ἀνακλινεῖ (anaklinei, "cause to recline") depicts the formal banquet posture, evoking the eschatological messianic banquet (Isa 25:6-8).',
        46: 'GREEK: διχοτομήσει (dichotomēsei, Strong\'s G1371) literally means "shall cut in two" — a hapax legomenon in the Gospels (also Matt 24:51). The severity of the image likely draws on ancient Near Eastern punishment for covenant violation. THEOLOGICAL: The pairing of cutting asunder with assigning a portion "with the unfaithful" (μετὰ τῶν ἀπίστων) indicates both judgment and permanent exclusion. The unexpectedness of the lord\'s return underscores the eschatological urgency of faithful stewardship.',
        48: 'THEOLOGICAL: This verse establishes a principle of proportional judgment: greater knowledge entails greater accountability. The distinction between the servant who knew and the one who did not know reveals graduated divine justice — God judges according to the light given. STRUCTURE: The concluding aphorism ("to whom much was given, much shall be required") forms a chiastic summary of the entire stewardship section (vv. 42-48), linking privilege to responsibility.',
        49: 'GREEK: πῦρ (pyr, "fire") here is ambiguous — it may refer to the fire of judgment (Mal 3:2-3), the refining fire of the Spirit (Acts 2:3), or the fire of division that Christ\'s coming provokes. THEOLOGICAL: Jesus expresses an intense desire (τί θέλω, "how I wish") for this fire to be kindled, revealing his awareness of the eschatological crisis his mission inaugurates. This connects to John the Baptist\'s prophecy of one who baptizes "with the Holy Spirit and fire" (Luke 3:16).',
        50: 'THEOLOGICAL: The βάπτισμα (baptisma, "baptism") Jesus must undergo is his suffering and death (cf. Mark 10:38-39). The verb συνέχομαι (synechomai, "I am constrained/pressed") reveals the intense inner pressure Jesus experienced as he moved toward the cross. TYPOLOGY: This baptism of death fulfills the pattern of passing through waters as judgment and deliverance — the Red Sea crossing (Exod 14), the Jordan crossing (Josh 3), and now the ultimate passage through death itself.',
        53: 'TYPOLOGY: The list of divided family members echoes Micah 7:6, a prophetic text describing the corruption of Israel before God\'s vindication. Jesus\' appropriation of this passage signals that his coming inaugurates the eschatological crisis Micah foresaw. THEOLOGICAL: Allegiance to Christ supersedes even the most fundamental human bonds, redefining kinship around faith rather than blood.',
        56: 'GREEK: ὑποκριταί (hypokritai) — the same root as ὑπόκρισις in v.1, forming an inclusio. The crowd can "discern" (δοκιμάζειν, dokimazein, Strong\'s G1381, meaning to test, prove, or examine) weather patterns but cannot discern the present καιρός (kairos) — the decisive, appointed time of God\'s action in Christ. THEOLOGICAL: The inability to read the signs of the times is a moral and spiritual failure, not merely an intellectual one.',
        59: 'GREEK: λεπτόν (lepton, Strong\'s G3016) was the smallest copper coin in circulation, worth roughly 1/128 of a denarius — the absolute minimum unit of currency. THEOLOGICAL: The parable of the adversary functions as a warning about eschatological judgment: settle accounts now, for divine justice is thorough and exacting. The imagery of imprisonment until the last coin is repaid underscores the completeness and inescapability of God\'s righteous judgment.',
    },
    13: {
        1: 'HISTORICAL: This incident of Pilate mingling Galilean blood with their sacrifices is not recorded in Josephus or other extra-biblical sources, though it is consistent with Pilate\'s known brutality. The act of defiling worshippers\' blood with their own sacrifices constituted an extreme sacrilege, violating the sanctity of the temple altar. This likely occurred during a festival pilgrimage when Galileans came to Jerusalem to offer sacrifice.',
        3: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus overturns the common Second Temple assumption that extraordinary suffering indicates extraordinary sin. The call to repentance (μετανοέω, metanoeō, Strong\'s G3340—a complete change of mind and orientation) is universal, not reserved for conspicuous sinners. The verb ἀπολεῖσθε (apoleisthe, "you will perish") carries both temporal and eschatological weight.',
        4: 'HISTORICAL: The tower in Siloam (Σιλωάμ) was located in the southeastern section of Jerusalem near the Pool of Siloam. This collapse is otherwise unattested in ancient sources. The term ὀφειλέται (opheiletai, "debtors," Strong\'s G3781) frames sin as a debt owed to God, consistent with Jewish theological vocabulary (cf. Matt 6:12).',
        7: 'TYPOLOGY: The fig tree in the vineyard echoes Israel as God\'s planting (Isa 5:1-7; Jer 8:13; Hos 9:10). The three years likely correspond to the duration of Jesus\' public ministry. The vinedresser\'s intercession prefigures Christ\'s own intercessory role on behalf of unfruitful Israel. The term ἀμπελουργόν (ampelourgon, "vinedresser," Strong\'s G289) is a compound of ἄμπελος (vine) and ἔργον (work)—a NT hapax legomenon.',
        11: 'GREEK: The phrase πνεῦμα ἀσθενείας (pneuma astheneias, "spirit of infirmity") indicates a demonic cause behind the physical condition, confirmed in v.16 where Satan is named as the agent of bondage. The verb συγκύπτουσα (synkyptousa, Strong\'s G4794, "bent together") is a NT hapax legomenon describing severe spinal curvature. DIVINE_COUNCIL: This passage reveals the intersection of the spiritual and physical realms—a spirit-being under Satan\'s authority producing bodily affliction.',
        16: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus designates the woman as a "daughter of Abraham" (θυγατέρα Ἀβραάμ), asserting her covenant membership and dignity against the synagogue ruler\'s dehumanizing disregard. The verb ἔδησεν (edēsen, "bound," Strong\'s G1210) directly parallels λυθῆναι (lythēnai, "be loosed"), framing the healing as liberation from Satanic bondage. DIVINE_COUNCIL: Satan\'s binding authority over a covenant member for eighteen years demonstrates the reality of hostile spiritual powers operating against God\'s people, which Christ has authority to overrule.',
        19: 'TYPOLOGY: The image of birds lodging in branches echoes Daniel 4:12 (Nebuchadnezzar\'s tree-kingdom) and Ezekiel 17:23; 31:6, where a great tree sheltering birds represents a kingdom encompassing the nations. The κόκκῳ σινάπεως (kokkō sinapeōs, "grain of mustard") is the smallest cultivated seed in Palestine, making the contrast between origin and outcome dramatic. The kingdom of God begins in hiddenness but achieves universal scope.',
        24: 'GREEK: Ἀγωνίζεσθε (agōnizesthe, Strong\'s G75) derives from ἀγών (agōn, "contest, struggle"), carrying the force of athletic or military exertion—not passive entry but intense striving. The στενῆς θύρας (stenēs thyras, "narrow door") differs from Matthew\'s "narrow gate" (πύλη, Matt 7:13-14); θύρα (Strong\'s G2374) specifically denotes a door to a house, fitting the householder parable that follows. THEOLOGICAL: The many who seek but cannot enter indicates that mere desire or association with Jesus is insufficient without genuine repentance.',
        27: 'TYPOLOGY: The phrase ἐργάται ἀδικίας ("workers of unrighteousness") echoes Psalm 6:8 (LXX Ps 6:9), where David commands evildoers to depart from him. Jesus here assumes the divine prerogative of the final Judge who determines covenant membership. The repeated "I do not know you, from where you are" constitutes a formal judicial disavowal.',
        29: 'THEOLOGICAL: The ingathering from the four compass points fulfills the prophetic vision of the nations streaming to Zion (Isa 2:2-3; 25:6-8; 49:12). The verb ἀνακλιθήσονται (anaklithēsontai, "will recline at table") evokes the eschatological messianic banquet. This is a radical inclusion of Gentiles alongside the patriarchs, while those who presumed covenant privilege are excluded.',
        32: 'GREEK: The term ἀλώπεκι (alōpeki, "fox," Strong\'s G258) denotes cunning and insignificance rather than power—a deliberate insult to Herod Antipas. THEOLOGICAL: The phrase τῇ τρίτῃ τελειοῦμαι ("on the third day I am perfected/completed," Strong\'s G5048) carries deep christological weight, pointing to the resurrection as the completion of Christ\'s redemptive work (cf. Heb 2:10; 5:9). Jesus declares sovereign control over his own timetable against any earthly ruler.',
        34: 'TYPOLOGY: Jesus\' lament over Jerusalem employs the maternal image of a hen (ὄρνις, ornis) gathering her brood (νοσσιάν, nossian) under her wings (πτέρυγας, pterygas), echoing the divine wing imagery of Deuteronomy 32:11, Ruth 2:12, and Psalm 91:4, where God shelters Israel under his wings. By applying this image to himself, Jesus claims the role of YHWH as protector of his people. THEOLOGICAL: The repeated vocative "Jerusalem, Jerusalem" parallels the prophetic double address of lament (cf. 2 Sam 18:33). The statement "you were not willing" (οὐκ ἠθελήσατε) places responsibility squarely on Jerusalem\'s corporate refusal.',
        35: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Your house is left to you" (ἀφίεται ὑμῖν ὁ οἶκος ὑμῶν) echoes Jeremiah 22:5 and 12:7, signifying the departure of divine presence from the temple—the Shekinah withdrawal. TYPOLOGY: The citation of Psalm 118:26 ("Blessed is he who comes in the name of the Lord") identifies Jesus as the Coming One of messianic expectation. The conditional "until" (ἕως) implies a future recognition, pointing toward Israel\'s eschatological repentance and acknowledgment of their Messiah (cf. Rom 11:25-26; Zech 12:10).',
    },
    14: {
        1: 'GREEK: The verb παρατηρούμενοι (paratēroumenoi, from παρατηρέω, Strong\'s G3906) carries the sense of watching closely with hostile intent, not casual observation. It denotes suspicious, scrutinizing surveillance. HISTORICAL: Dining at a Pharisaic ruler\'s home on the Sabbath was a formal occasion; meals followed synagogue services and were governed by strict purity regulations.',
        2: 'GREEK: ὑδρωπικός (hydrōpikos, G5203) is a hapax legomenon in the New Testament, appearing only here. It refers to a condition of abnormal fluid retention (dropsy/edema). HISTORICAL: Some rabbinical traditions associated dropsy with sinfulness, which may explain the test being set before Jesus on the Sabbath.',
        5: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus employs a qal wahomer (lesser to greater) argument common in rabbinical discourse. If compassion compels rescue of a son or even an animal on the Sabbath, how much more should a suffering human being be healed? The textual variant between "son" (υἱός) and "donkey" (ὄνος) is significant; the harder reading "son" is likely original.',
        11: 'THEOLOGICAL: This principle of divine reversal is a central theme in Luke\'s Gospel (Luke 1:52; 18:14). The passive verbs ταπεινωθήσεται and ὑψωθήσεται are divine passives—God is the unstated agent who humbles the proud and exalts the humble. TYPOLOGY: This echoes Proverbs 25:6-7 and anticipates the exaltation of Christ through his own humiliation (Phil 2:8-9).',
        14: 'THEOLOGICAL: The phrase ἐν τῇ ἀναστάσει τῶν δικαίων ("in the resurrection of the righteous") presupposes a Pharisaic eschatology of bodily resurrection, which Jesus here affirms. This implies a distinction between the resurrection of the righteous and a general resurrection, consistent with Daniel 12:2 and Revelation 20:5-6.',
        15: 'HISTORICAL: The guest\'s exclamation reflects a common Jewish eschatological expectation of the Messianic banquet (Isa 25:6-8). The phrase "eat bread in the kingdom of God" evokes the image of table fellowship in the age to come. Jesus\' response in the following parable challenges the assumption that all Israel would automatically participate.',
        21: 'TYPOLOGY: The master\'s command to bring in the poor, maimed, blind, and lame from the city streets echoes the categories from v.13 and reverses the exclusions of 2 Samuel 5:8. Those barred from the temple are now welcomed to the Lord\'s table. THEOLOGICAL: The progression from city streets (v.21) to highways and hedges (v.23) typologically represents the extension of God\'s invitation from Israel to the Gentiles (Acts 13:46).',
        24: 'THEOLOGICAL: The shift from third person parable to first person "I say to you" (λέγω γὰρ ὑμῖν) is striking—it suggests Jesus speaks not merely as narrator but as the Lord of the feast himself. This is a solemn warning of eschatological exclusion for those who refuse the divine invitation. TYPOLOGY: The Great Supper parable parallels Matthew 22:1-14 but with distinctly Lukan emphases on the marginalized.',
        26: 'GREEK: μισεῖ (miseī, G3404) "hate" is a Semitic idiom of preference and comparative priority, not emotional hatred (cf. Gen 29:31; Mal 1:2-3). Jesus demands that loyalty to him surpass all natural bonds, including one\'s own ψυχή (psychē)—life, soul, self. THEOLOGICAL: The radical nature of discipleship here reflects the absolute claim of the Messiah-King over every allegiance.',
        27: 'THEOLOGICAL: βαστάζει τὸν σταυρὸν ἑαυτοῦ ("bears his own cross") is spoken before the crucifixion, yet prefigures Christ\'s own path. For the original audience, this evoked the Roman practice of condemned criminals carrying the crossbeam (patibulum) to execution—a summons to total self-denial unto death (Luke 9:23).',
        33: 'GREEK: ἀποτάσσεται (apotassetai, G657) means "to take leave of" or "to renounce, bid farewell to." It connotes a decisive, final separation from one\'s possessions. THEOLOGICAL: This verse serves as the interpretive key to both preceding parables (tower builder and warring king): discipleship requires a sober reckoning of total cost and total surrender.',
        35: 'THEOLOGICAL: Salt that has lost its savor (μωρανθῇ, from μωραίνω, G3471, also meaning "to become foolish") becomes utterly useless—fit neither for land nor for manure. This is a warning against nominal discipleship. STRUCTURE: The closing formula "He who has ears to hear, let him hear" (cf. Mark 4:9; Rev 2:7) signals that the entire chapter—Sabbath healing, banquet teachings, cost of discipleship—forms a unified discourse demanding a decisive response.',
    },
    15: {
        2: 'GREEK: διεγόγγυζον (diagongyzō, Strong\'s G1234) is an intensified form of γογγύζω, indicating persistent, thorough murmuring — not a single complaint but a sustained grumbling. The prefix δια- intensifies the action. HISTORICAL: Table fellowship in Second Temple Judaism was a covenant marker; eating with sinners was not merely a social faux pas but a perceived violation of holiness boundaries (cf. Gal 2:12).',
        4: 'TYPOLOGY: The shepherd seeking the lost sheep echoes Ezekiel 34:11-16, where God himself declares he will search for his scattered sheep, in contrast to the faithless shepherds of Israel. Jesus implicitly identifies himself with YHWH as the true Shepherd (cf. Ps 23:1; John 10:11). GREEK: ἀπολωλός (apolōlos) is the perfect active participle of ἀπόλλυμι — the sheep is in a state of having been lost, emphasizing its ongoing condition of lostness.',
        7: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus establishes a startling heavenly economy of joy: heaven\'s celebration is disproportionately directed toward the repentant sinner rather than the already-righteous. This directly addresses the Pharisees\' grumbling in v.2. GREEK: μετανοοῦντι (metanoounti) — present active participle of μετανοέω (Strong\'s G3340), literally "changing one\'s mind," indicating a turning of the whole orientation of life, not merely feeling sorry.',
        10: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: The phrase ἐνώπιον τῶν ἀγγέλων τοῦ θεοῦ ("before the angels of God") reveals the heavenly court setting — the divine council witnesses and rejoices at the repentance of sinners. Joy originates in the presence of God himself, with the angels as the attending assembly (cf. Job 1:6; Ps 89:7; Dan 7:10). THEOLOGICAL: The formulation suggests that the ultimate source of joy is God himself; the angels are witnesses before whom the joy occurs.',
        13: 'GREEK: ἀσώτως (asōtōs, Strong\'s G811) is a NT hapax legomenon, meaning "dissolutely" or "wastefully" — literally "unsavingly," from the alpha-privative + σῴζω (to save). It describes a manner of life that is beyond saving or recovery. HISTORICAL: Traveling to a "far country" (χώραν μακράν) implies leaving the land of Israel, thus abandoning covenant community and placing oneself among Gentiles.',
        16: 'HISTORICAL: κερατίων (keratia) refers to carob pods, the fruit of the Ceratonia siliqua tree, used commonly as animal feed in the Mediterranean world. THEOLOGICAL: Feeding swine represents the nadir of Jewish degradation, as pigs were ritually unclean animals (Lev 11:7). That no one gave to him underscores his complete desolation and alienation from all human community.',
        20: 'GREEK: ἐσπλαγχνίσθη (esplanchnisthē, Strong\'s G4697) — from σπλάγχνα, the inward parts or bowels, regarded as the seat of deep emotion. This is the same verb used of Jesus\' compassion (Matt 9:36; Mark 1:41). κατεφίλησεν (katephilēsen) is an intensified form of φιλέω with the prefix κατα-, indicating fervent, repeated kissing. TYPOLOGY: The father\'s running is culturally extraordinary — a dignified patriarch in the ancient Near East would not run, suggesting a deliberate self-humiliation that prefigures God\'s condescension in Christ.',
        22: 'TYPOLOGY: The robe (στολὴν τὴν πρώτην — "the first/best robe"), the ring (δακτύλιον), and sandals (ὑποδήματα) together signify full restoration: the robe indicates honor and status, the ring signifies authority and family identity (cf. Gen 41:42), and sandals distinguish a son from a slave, who would go barefoot. THEOLOGICAL: This is not partial acceptance but complete reinstatement — the imagery of royal investiture echoes God\'s restoration of Israel (cf. Zech 3:4-5, where Joshua the high priest is reclothed).',
        24: 'THEOLOGICAL: The death-to-life and lost-to-found language carries profound theological weight, anticipating the Pauline theology of resurrection from spiritual death (Eph 2:1-5; Col 2:13). GREEK: ἀνέζησεν (anezēsen) — "came to life again," from ἀναζάω, emphasizing not merely survival but a genuine return from death to life. The father\'s declaration functions as a performative utterance establishing the son\'s new status.',
        32: 'THEOLOGICAL: ἔδει (edei) — "it was necessary/fitting" — introduces divine necessity. The father does not merely choose to celebrate; it is a moral and theological imperative. The parable ends without resolution regarding the elder son — an open ending directed at the Pharisees and scribes of v.2, inviting them to respond. STRUCTURE: The three parables of Luke 15 form a unified triptych with escalating intimacy: a shepherd with sheep, a woman with a coin, a father with a son — each revealing God\'s relentless pursuit and extravagant joy over the lost who are found.',
    },
    16: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Steward" (οἰκονόμος, oikonomos, Strong\'s G3623) denotes a household manager or estate administrator—one entrusted with another\'s property. The term carries weight in Pauline theology as well (1 Cor 4:1-2; Tit 1:7). "Squandering" (διασκορπίζων, diaskorpizōn) is the same verb used of the prodigal son in Luke 15:13, linking the two parables thematically.',
        6: 'HISTORICAL: A "bath" (βάτος, batos) was a Hebrew liquid measure of approximately 22 liters (roughly 6 gallons). One hundred baths of oil represented a substantial debt. The reduction to fifty—a fifty percent discount—would have created significant goodwill and social obligation from the debtor toward the steward.',
        7: 'HISTORICAL: A "cor" (κόρος, koros) was a Hebrew dry measure equivalent to approximately 10-11 bushels. One hundred cors of wheat was an enormous quantity. The reduction to eighty—a twenty percent discount—was proportionally smaller than the oil reduction, perhaps reflecting different profit margins.',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The lord" (ὁ κύριος) here refers to the master in the parable, not to Jesus or God. The commendation is not for dishonesty but for shrewdness (φρονίμως, phronimōs). The contrast between "sons of this age" and "sons of light" echoes the language of Qumran (1QS 1:9; 3:13) and Pauline usage (1 Thess 5:5; Eph 5:8). DIVINE_COUNCIL: The "sons of light" designation implies a cosmic-spiritual allegiance, contrasting those aligned with God\'s realm against those operating by worldly wisdom.',
        9: 'GREEK: "Mammon" (μαμωνᾶς, mamōnas) is an Aramaic loanword meaning wealth or property, here personified as a rival power. "Eternal dwellings" (αἰωνίους σκηνάς) deliberately echoes the tabernacle/tent (σκηνή) language of the LXX, pointing to eschatological habitations prepared by God. THEOLOGICAL: Jesus commands the strategic, generous use of worldly wealth for eternal relational gain—an inversion of the steward\'s self-serving shrewdness.',
        13: 'GREEK: "Household servant" (οἰκέτης, oiketēs, Strong\'s G3610) is more specific than the general δοῦλος (doulos); it denotes a domestic slave, intensifying the intimacy of the service relationship. THEOLOGICAL: The parallel in Matt 6:24 omits οἰκέτης. The absolute impossibility of dual service frames mammon as a functional deity competing with the true God for total allegiance (cf. Deut 6:4-5).',
        15: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Abomination" (βδέλυγμα, bdelygma, Strong\'s G946) is the LXX term for idolatrous defilement (cf. Dan 9:27; 11:31; 12:11). Jesus applies this cultic pollution language to human self-exaltation, equating the Pharisees\' honor-seeking with idolatry. What is "exalted" (ὑψηλόν) among men stands as detestable before God—a radical inversion of human value systems.',
        16: 'THEOLOGICAL: This verse marks a pivotal salvation-historical transition: the epoch of the Law and the Prophets finds its terminus ad quem in John the Baptist. From that point, the kingdom of God is "proclaimed as good news" (εὐαγγελίζεται, euangelizetai). TYPOLOGY: John the Baptist functions as the Elijah figure (Mal 4:5; Luke 1:17) who heralds the new era. The verb βιάζεται can be middle ("forces his way in") or passive ("is being forced"), with the former reading emphasizing the urgency of kingdom entry.',
        22: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The bosom of Abraham" (τὸν κόλπον Ἀβραάμ) denotes a place of honor and intimate fellowship at the eschatological banquet (cf. John 13:23 for the same idiom). This reflects Second Temple Jewish belief in a differentiated intermediate state. HISTORICAL: The imagery of angels carrying the righteous dead is attested in Jewish tradition (Testament of Abraham; 4 Maccabees). The rich man receives only burial—no angelic escort.',
        23: 'GREEK: "Hades" (ᾅδης, hadēs, Strong\'s G86) translates Hebrew Sheol and in this context denotes the abode of the unrighteous dead in conscious torment, distinct from the place of comfort where Abraham and Lazarus reside. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The passage reflects a cosmology in which the dead exist in a differentiated intermediate state under divine governance, awaiting final judgment.',
        26: 'THEOLOGICAL: The "great chasm" (χάσμα μέγα) that has been "fixed" (ἐστήρικται, perfect passive of στηρίζω) indicates a permanent, divinely established boundary. The perfect tense emphasizes the settled, irrevocable nature of this separation. This excludes any post-mortem crossing or second chance, underscoring the finality of one\'s state after death.',
        29: 'TYPOLOGY: "Moses and the Prophets" constitutes the entirety of the Hebrew Scriptures as witness to God\'s covenant faithfulness and ethical demands. Abraham\'s response places supreme authority in the written Word of God over miraculous signs—a theme central to Luke\'s theology (Luke 24:25-27, 44-45).',
        31: 'TYPOLOGY: This climactic verse carries profound irony: one named Lazarus will indeed be raised from the dead (John 11:1-44), and the religious leaders will not believe but will plot to kill both Jesus and Lazarus (John 11:53; 12:10). Ultimately, Jesus himself rises from the dead, and still many refuse to believe. The sufficiency of Scripture as witness to Christ is thus powerfully affirmed (cf. John 5:39-47).',
    },
    17: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Anendekton" (ἀνένδεκτον) is a NT hapax legomenon meaning "inadmissible, impossible." "Skandala" (σκάνδαλα, Strong\'s G4625) refers to a trap-stick or stumbling-block—an occasion that causes spiritual ruin. The term carries connotations of entrapment in both moral and spiritual senses.',
        2: 'GREEK: "Lithos mylikos" (λίθος μυλικός) refers to a large millstone turned by a donkey, not a small hand-mill stone. The hyperbolic image emphasizes the catastrophic severity of leading a "little one" (mikros) astray. THEOLOGICAL: The "little ones" likely refers to new or vulnerable believers whose faith can be destroyed by the stumbling-blocks of verse 1.',
        5: 'GREEK: "Prosthes" (πρόσθες) is an aorist imperative of prostithēmi—"Add!" The apostles recognize that the demands of limitless forgiveness (v.4) exceed natural human capacity and require a divine grant of faith. This is the only place in Luke where "apostoloi" address Jesus as "Kyrios" in a direct petition.',
        6: 'GREEK: "Kokkos sinapeōs" (κόκκον σινάπεως)—a grain of mustard, proverbially the smallest of seeds. "Sykaminos" (συκαμίνος, G4807) is the black mulberry tree, distinct from the sycamore-fig (sykomoros) of Luke 19:4. THEOLOGICAL: Jesus does not promise to increase their faith quantitatively; he redefines faith as operative trust in God\'s power, where even a minuscule measure can accomplish the impossible.',
        10: 'GREEK: "Achreioi douloi" (ἀχρεῖοι δοῦλοι)—"unprofitable servants" or "unworthy servants." The word achreios (G888) means "useless" in the sense of having no claim to special merit. THEOLOGICAL: This parable establishes that obedience to God\'s commands creates no basis for boasting or meritorious standing; the servant has merely fulfilled obligation. This anticipates Pauline grace theology (Rom 4:4-5; Eph 2:8-9).',
        14: 'TYPOLOGY: Jesus commands the lepers to show themselves to the priests according to the Torah purification rite of Leviticus 14:1-32. Their cleansing occurs en route—while obeying in faith before the evidence appears. This prefigures justification by faith: acting on the word of Christ before visible confirmation. HISTORICAL: That the group included a Samaritan (v.16) is remarkable, as Samaritans would not normally travel with Jews to Jerusalem\'s temple priests.',
        18: 'GREEK: "Allogenēs" (ἀλλογενής, G241) is a NT hapax legomenon meaning "of another race/nation, foreigner." Strikingly, this exact word appears on the Jerusalem temple warning inscription forbidding non-Jews from entering the inner courts. THEOLOGICAL: The irony is devastating—the one whom the temple placard would exclude as allogenēs is the only one who returns to glorify God. This foreshadows the inclusion of the Gentiles and the obsolescence of ethnic barriers in the kingdom.',
        21: 'GREEK: "Entos hymōn" (ἐντὸς ὑμῶν) can mean either "within you" (interior/spiritual) or "in your midst" (among you). Given that Jesus addresses hostile Pharisees, "in your midst" is the more likely sense—the kingdom is present because the King himself stands among them. THEOLOGICAL: The kingdom of God is not a geopolitical event to be charted by observation (paratērēsis, G3907) but is inaugurated in the person and authority of Jesus the Christ.',
        24: 'THEOLOGICAL: The Son of Man\'s revelation (apokalypsis) will be unmistakable and universal—like lightning illuminating the entire sky. No secret or localized coming is in view. TYPOLOGY: The "Son of Man" title draws from Daniel 7:13-14, where one like a son of man receives dominion, glory, and an everlasting kingdom from the Ancient of Days. DIVINE_COUNCIL: This evokes the heavenly court scene of Daniel 7, where the Son of Man is enthroned above the hostile beast-kingdoms.',
        25: 'THEOLOGICAL: Before the glory of revelation comes the necessity (dei, δεῖ—divine necessity) of suffering and rejection. This is the pattern of Christ\'s messianic vocation: suffering precedes glory, the cross before the crown. This verse anchors the eschatological discourse in the immediate reality of the passion (cf. Luke 9:22, 18:31-33).',
        29: 'TYPOLOGY: The destruction of Sodom by fire and brimstone (theion, θεῖον) from heaven serves as a type of the eschatological judgment at the Son of Man\'s revelation. DIVINE_COUNCIL: Genesis 19:24 describes YHWH raining fire "from YHWH out of heaven," a passage long noted in Jewish exegesis as indicating a two-powers-in-heaven theology. Jesus applies this divine judgment pattern to his own coming as the Son of Man.',
        32: 'TYPOLOGY: Lot\'s wife (Gen 19:26) looked back toward Sodom and became a pillar of salt. She serves as a negative type of attachment to the world that is under judgment. Her backward glance represents divided loyalty—the antithesis of the total surrender demanded in v.33.',
        33: 'GREEK: "Zōogonēsei" (ζῳογονήσει, G2225) literally means "shall bring to life, shall give life to." This is a rare and vivid term, stronger than simply "save." THEOLOGICAL: The paradox of the kingdom: self-preservation leads to destruction, while self-loss for Christ\'s sake leads to the generation of true, eschatological life. This echoes Luke 9:24 and anticipates the theology of dying and rising with Christ (Rom 6:4-5).',
        37: 'GREEK: "Aetoi" (ἀετοί, G105) can mean either "eagles" or "vultures." In context, the proverb points to vultures gathering where a corpse lies—judgment is drawn inevitably to the place of spiritual death. THEOLOGICAL: The disciples ask "Where?" regarding the coming judgment. Jesus answers with a proverb rather than a location: judgment is not a matter of geography but of spiritual condition. Where moral corruption exists, divine judgment will inevitably descend.',
    },
    18: {
        1: 'GREEK: The verb ἐγκακεῖν (enkakein, Strong\'s G1573) means "to lose heart, become weary, faint." The construction πρὸς τὸ δεῖν with the infinitive expresses purpose — literally "toward the being necessary." This sets the entire parable as instruction on persistent prayer. STRUCTURE: This parable (vv. 1-8) and the one following (vv. 9-14) form a pair on prayer, the first addressing perseverance, the second addressing posture of heart.',
        5: 'GREEK: The verb ὑπωπιάζῃ (hypōpiazē, Strong\'s G5299) literally means "to strike under the eye, give a black eye." It is a vivid boxing metaphor meaning "to wear out completely." The same word appears in 1 Cor 9:27 where Paul describes disciplining his body. This is a rare and colorful term emphasizing the relentless, almost physically exhausting nature of the widow\'s persistence.',
        7: 'THEOLOGICAL: The argument proceeds from lesser to greater (qal wahomer): if an unrighteous judge yields to persistence, how much more will the righteous God vindicate His chosen ones? The term ἐκλεκτῶν (eklektōn, "elect/chosen," Strong\'s G1588) carries covenant significance — God\'s own people set apart by His sovereign choice. GREEK: μακροθυμεῖ (makrothymei, Strong\'s G3114) means "to be long-suffering, patient," suggesting God\'s patience is not delay but purposeful restraint.',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: The question about the Son of Man finding "the faith" (τὴν πίστιν, with the definite article) upon the earth is profoundly eschatological. It implies not merely generic belief but the specific, persevering faith described in this parable. TYPOLOGY: "The Son of Man coming" echoes Daniel 7:13-14, where the Son of Man receives dominion and a kingdom from the Ancient of Days — a divine council scene of enthronement and vindication (Dan 7:13-14).',
        13: 'GREEK: The verb ἱλάσθητί (hilasthēti, Strong\'s G2433) is an aorist passive imperative of ἱλάσκομαι — "be propitiated toward me" or "be merciful." This is sacrificial language rooted in the LXX atonement vocabulary (cf. Lev 16). The definite article τῷ before ἁμαρτωλῷ ("the sinner") is emphatic — he identifies himself as the sinner par excellence. TYPOLOGY: This prayer echoes Psalm 51:1 (LXX 50:3), David\'s great penitential cry, and anticipates the propitiatory work of Christ (Rom 3:25; Heb 2:17).',
        14: 'THEOLOGICAL: The verb δεδικαιωμένος (dedikaiōmenos, perfect passive participle of δικαιόω, Strong\'s G1344) means "having been justified/declared righteous." This is a forensic legal term — God as judge declares the repentant sinner righteous. This verse is foundational for the doctrine of justification by grace through humility and faith rather than by self-righteous works (cf. Rom 3:24-28; Gal 2:16). The reversal principle stated here echoes the Magnificat (Luke 1:52).',
        17: 'THEOLOGICAL: The double negative οὐ μὴ (ou mē) with the subjunctive εἰσέλθῃ constitutes the strongest possible negation in Greek — "shall absolutely not enter." Receiving the kingdom "as a little child" (ὡς παιδίον) denotes not innocence but receptive dependence and lack of self-sufficiency — the same posture as the tax collector in v. 13, contrasted with the self-trusting Pharisee and the rich ruler who follows.',
        19: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus does not deny His own goodness or deity but redirects the ruler\'s superficial use of "good" to its ultimate theological ground. If only God is truly good (ἀγαθός, agathos), and Jesus is truly good, the implication presses toward His divine identity. This is a pedagogical challenge, not a denial of divinity (cf. John 10:30; Col 1:19). GREEK: The construction εἰ μὴ εἷς ὁ θεός recalls the Shema — "the Lord our God, the Lord is One" (Deut 6:4 LXX).',
        25: 'GREEK: The word τρήματος (trēmatos, Strong\'s G5169) means "hole, eye (of a needle)," and βελόνης (belonēs, Strong\'s G956) refers specifically to a sewing needle, not a gate. This is deliberate hyperbole — a literal impossibility — emphasizing that wealth creates a humanly insurmountable barrier to entering God\'s kingdom. HISTORICAL: Some later interpreters invented a small gate called "the eye of the needle" in Jerusalem, but no archaeological or literary evidence from the period supports this. The hyperbole is the point.',
        27: 'THEOLOGICAL: This verse is the theological pivot of the passage. Salvation is not a human achievement but a divine possibility. The term ἀδύνατα (adynata, "impossible things") paired with δυνατά (dynata, "possible things") establishes that entry into the kingdom is wholly a work of God\'s power and grace, not human moral effort (cf. Gen 18:14 LXX; Jer 32:17).',
        31: 'TYPOLOGY: This is the third and most detailed passion prediction in Luke (cf. Luke 9:22, 9:44). The phrase "all the things that have been written through the prophets" (πάντα τὰ γεγραμμένα διὰ τῶν προφητῶν) affirms that the suffering of the Son of Man is not failure but prophetic fulfillment — Isaiah 53, Psalm 22, Zechariah 12:10 all converge on the Messiah\'s suffering and vindication. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The Son of Man title (Dan 7:13-14) designates a heavenly figure who receives authority from the Ancient of Days within the divine council assembly, yet this same figure must first suffer — a mystery hidden from the disciples (v. 34).',
        34: 'THEOLOGICAL: The threefold emphasis on incomprehension — "understood none," "this word was hidden," "did not comprehend" — underscores the divinely concealed nature of the Messiah\'s suffering. The passive κεκρυμμένον ("having been hidden") may imply divine agency: God Himself veiled the meaning until after the resurrection (cf. Luke 24:25-27, 44-46). The disciples\' inability mirrors Israel\'s hardness described in Isaiah 6:9-10.',
        38: 'TYPOLOGY: The cry "Son of David" (Υἱὲ Δαυίδ) is a messianic title rooted in the Davidic covenant (2 Sam 7:12-16). This blind beggar confesses what the disciples cannot yet comprehend — that Jesus is the promised Davidic King. The plea ἐλέησόν με ("have mercy on me") echoes the psalmic cries of the afflicted to God (Ps 6:2; 51:1 LXX). THEOLOGICAL: It is deeply ironic that a physically blind man sees Jesus\' messianic identity while the sighted disciples remain spiritually blind (v. 34).',
        42: 'GREEK: The verb σέσωκέν (sesōken, perfect active of σῴζω, Strong\'s G4982) means both "has saved" and "has healed/made whole." The perfect tense indicates a completed action with ongoing results. Faith (πίστις) is the instrument, but the power is Christ\'s alone. THEOLOGICAL: Physical healing serves as a sign of the greater salvation Jesus brings — the restoration of all things. The blind receiving sight fulfills the messianic program announced in Luke 4:18 (Isa 61:1-2).',
    },
    19: {
        2: 'GREEK: ἀρχιτελώνης (architelōnēs) is a NT hapax legomenon, occurring only here. It denotes a "chief tax-collector" — one who supervised other tax-collectors (telōnai) in a district. Jericho was a lucrative taxation hub due to balsam trade and its position on a major trade route. HISTORICAL: Tax-collectors (publicani) contracted with Rome and were despised as collaborators and extortioners. A chief tax-collector would have been especially wealthy and socially ostracized among Jews.',
        5: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus initiates the encounter with divine necessity — δεῖ (dei, "it is necessary") signals divine compulsion, not mere convenience. Jesus declares he "must" (dei) stay at Zacchaeus\'s house, indicating this visit fulfills the divine plan. The seeking belongs to Christ, not the sinner (cf. v.10). GREEK: μεῖναι (meinai, "to remain/abide") carries Johannine overtones of intimate fellowship (cf. John 15:4).',
        8: 'GREEK: σταθείς (statheis, aorist passive participle of ἵστημι) — "having stood," indicating a formal, solemn posture of public declaration. τετραπλοῦν (tetraploun, "fourfold") exceeds the Torah requirement of restoring the principal plus one-fifth (Lev 6:5; Num 5:7), matching instead the penalty for theft of a sheep (Exod 22:1 LXX). THEOLOGICAL: Zacchaeus addresses Jesus as κύριε (kyrie, "Lord"), recognizing his authority. His restitution demonstrates genuine repentance bearing fruit (cf. Luke 3:8).',
        10: 'THEOLOGICAL: This verse encapsulates Jesus\'s mission statement in Luke. ζητῆσαι καὶ σῶσαι τὸ ἀπολωλός ("to seek and to save the lost") echoes Ezekiel 34:16 where God himself declares he will seek the lost sheep — a shepherd-king function. Jesus claims for himself the role prophesied for YHWH. TYPOLOGY: The Son of Man title (Dan 7:13-14) combined with the divine shepherd motif (Ezek 34) identifies Jesus as both the Danielic ruler and the God who personally rescues his flock.',
        12: 'HISTORICAL: The parable of the nobleman mirrors the historical journey of Archelaus, son of Herod the Great, who traveled to Rome in 4 BC to receive his kingdom from Augustus, while a Jewish embassy of fifty followed to oppose his appointment (Josephus, Ant. 17.11.1). Luke\'s audience would have recognized this political backdrop. TYPOLOGY: The nobleman going to a far country to receive a kingdom and return prefigures Christ\'s ascension and second coming. The kingdom is received from a higher authority — the Father (cf. Dan 7:13-14).',
        14: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: The citizens\' rejection — "We do not desire this man to reign over us" — echoes Israel\'s rejection of God\'s kingship in 1 Samuel 8:7. This pattern of rebellion against the divinely appointed ruler recurs throughout Scripture. THEOLOGICAL: This verse prophetically anticipates the Jewish leaders\' rejection of Jesus before Pilate: "We have no king but Caesar" (John 19:15).',
        27: 'THEOLOGICAL: The severe judgment — κατασφάξατε (katasphaxate, "slay/slaughter") — reflects the eschatological judgment upon those who reject the rightful King. This is no mere parable detail but a solemn pronouncement of the consequences of rejecting the Messiah\'s reign. TYPOLOGY: The destruction prefigures both the fall of Jerusalem in AD 70 and the final judgment at Christ\'s return.',
        38: 'TYPOLOGY: This acclamation combines Psalm 118:26 (LXX 117:26) — "Blessed is the one coming in the name of the Lord" — with the explicit addition of βασιλεύς (basileus, "King"), unique to Luke\'s account. The disciples publicly declare Jesus as the Davidic King. STRUCTURE: Luke substitutes "Peace in heaven and glory in the highest" for the Markan/Matthean "Hosanna," creating a deliberate parallel with the angelic proclamation at Jesus\'s birth (Luke 2:14): glory and peace now bracket his ministry.',
        40: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus affirms that his royal acclamation is not optional but cosmically necessary. If human voices are silenced, creation itself (the stones) will testify — echoing Habakkuk 2:11 where stones cry out against injustice. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The cosmic testimony of creation to its rightful King reflects the theology that all things were made through him and for him (Col 1:16), and creation groans for its redemption (Rom 8:19-22).',
        42: 'GREEK: The sentence breaks off mid-thought (aposiopesis) — "the things pertaining to peace—" is left incomplete, heightening the pathos. εἰρήνην (eirēnēn) is deeply ironic: Jerusalem (Yerushalayim) contains the root שָׁלוֹם (shalom, "peace"), yet the city of peace cannot recognize what would bring it peace. THEOLOGICAL: ἐκρύβη (ekrybē, "it was hidden," divine passive) suggests God himself has judicially hidden the knowledge from their eyes, recalling Isaiah 6:9-10.',
        44: 'HISTORICAL: ἐδαφιοῦσίν σε (edaphiousin se, "they will dash you to the ground") and the stone-upon-stone language precisely describe the Roman destruction of Jerusalem in AD 70 under Titus, when the city and temple were razed. GREEK: ἐπισκοπή (episkopē, "visitation") carries dual meaning — it can be a gracious visitation for salvation or a judicial visitation for judgment (cf. 1 Pet 2:12). Israel missed the former and received the latter. TYPOLOGY: This echoes the covenant pattern of Deuteronomy 28-32 — blessings for obedience, curses for rejecting God\'s appointed deliverer.',
        46: 'TYPOLOGY: Jesus combines Isaiah 56:7 ("my house shall be called a house of prayer") with Jeremiah 7:11 ("den of robbers"), both prophetic indictments of temple corruption. Just as Jeremiah warned of the first temple\'s destruction, Jesus warns of the second. THEOLOGICAL: By calling the temple "my house," Jesus implicitly claims divine prerogative — it is his Father\'s house and thus his own. The cleansing enacts prophetic authority over the temple itself (cf. Mal 3:1-3).',
        48: 'GREEK: ἐξεκρέματο (exekremato) is a vivid NT hapax legomenon meaning "was hanging upon" — the people hung on his every word, an image of rapt, absorbed attention. The imperfect tense conveys ongoing, continuous action. STRUCTURE: This verse sets the stage for the passion narrative: the leaders desire to kill Jesus but are restrained by the people\'s devotion, creating the dramatic tension that drives the subsequent chapters.',
    },
    20: {
        1: 'GREEK: ἐπέστησαν (epestēsan, from ἐφίστημι, "to come upon, stand over") conveys a sudden confrontation. The combination of chief priests, scribes, and elders represents the full Sanhedrin—the three constituent groups of the ruling council. HISTORICAL: This confrontation occurs during Jesus\'s final week of temple teaching, when his authority directly challenged the religious establishment\'s control of the temple precinct.',
        2: 'THEOLOGICAL: The question of ἐξουσία (exousia, "authority") is central to this chapter. The religious leaders demand Jesus name the source of his authority—whether rabbinic ordination, prophetic commission, or divine appointment. Jesus\'s counter-question reveals that they have already rejected the prophetic witness that would have answered their question (John 1:29-34).',
        4: 'TYPOLOGY: John\'s baptism as "from heaven" (ἐξ οὐρανοῦ) connects the prophetic office to divine commissioning. John served as the Elijah-figure preparing the way (Mal 3:1; Luke 1:17), and his testimony pointed directly to Jesus\'s authority as the Coming One. To acknowledge John was to acknowledge Jesus.',
        9: 'TYPOLOGY: The parable of the vineyard directly echoes Isaiah 5:1-7, where Israel is God\'s vineyard. The owner (God) entrusting it to vinedressers (Israel\'s leaders) establishes the covenant framework. The "considerable time" (χρόνους ἱκανούς) reflects the long span of salvation history from Sinai to the Second Temple period.',
        13: 'THEOLOGICAL: The phrase τὸν υἱόν μου τὸν ἀγαπητόν ("my beloved son") echoes the divine voice at Jesus\'s baptism (Luke 3:22) and transfiguration (Luke 9:35). The lord of the vineyard sending his son after the servants (prophets) establishes the Son\'s unique status above all prophetic messengers. TYPOLOGY: The pattern of rejected prophets culminating in the rejected Son fulfills the trajectory of 2 Chronicles 36:15-16.',
        17: 'TYPOLOGY: Jesus quotes Psalm 118:22 (LXX 117:22), the rejected stone becoming the cornerstone. This psalm was sung during Passover and Feast of Tabernacles processions. The rejected stone is a messianic image: Christ, rejected by Israel\'s builders (leaders), becomes the foundational stone of God\'s new temple (Eph 2:20; 1 Pet 2:4-7). GREEK: κεφαλὴν γωνίας (kephalēn gōnias, "head of the corner") denotes the capstone or keystone that holds the entire structure together.',
        18: 'THEOLOGICAL: This verse likely alludes to both Isaiah 8:14-15 (the stone of stumbling) and Daniel 2:34-35, 44-45 (the stone that crushes the kingdoms). The dual action—being shattered by falling on the stone, or being ground to powder when it falls—expresses the inescapable judgment of rejecting the Messiah. GREEK: λικμήσει (likmēsei, from λικμάω, "to winnow, scatter like chaff") is rare in the NT, intensifying the imagery of total destruction.',
        20: 'GREEK: ἐγκαθέτους (enkathetous, "planted agents, spies") is a NT hapax legomenon, found only here. It derives from ἐγκαθίημι ("to send in secretly"). HISTORICAL: The goal of delivering Jesus to the ἡγεμών (hēgemōn, "governor"—Pontius Pilate) shows the leaders sought a political charge, since only Rome could execute capital punishment in Judea at this time.',
        25: 'THEOLOGICAL: ἀπόδοτε (apodote, from ἀποδίδωμι, "render back, return what is owed") is more precise than simply "give"—it implies returning what belongs to its rightful owner. Caesar\'s image on the coin establishes his claim; but humanity bears God\'s image (Gen 1:26-27), establishing God\'s total claim over human beings. The answer transcends the political trap entirely.',
        36: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: ἰσάγγελοι (isangeloi, "equal to angels") is a NT hapax legomenon, occurring only here. The risen saints share the immortal nature of the heavenly beings. The phrase υἱοί εἰσιν θεοῦ ("they are sons of God") places resurrected believers within the divine council framework—they become members of the heavenly family, sharing the status of the "sons of God" (bene elohim) of the heavenly assembly (Job 1:6; Ps 89:6). THEOLOGICAL: Sonship is linked specifically to resurrection, connecting adoption to eschatological transformation (Rom 8:23).',
        37: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus argues for resurrection from the Torah itself (Exod 3:6), the only portion of Scripture the Sadducees accepted as fully authoritative. God\'s self-identification as the God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob in the present tense at the burning bush implies their continued existence. The covenant relationship endures beyond death. GREEK: ἐμήνυσεν (emēnysen, from μηνύω, "to disclose, reveal") suggests Moses made known a hidden truth about God\'s nature.',
        42: 'TYPOLOGY: Jesus quotes Psalm 110:1 (LXX 109:1), the most frequently cited OT passage in the NT. εἶπεν κύριος τῷ κυρίῳ μου—"The Lord said to my Lord"—in the Hebrew, YHWH speaks to the Davidic king addressed as אדני (adoni). Jesus\'s argument is that David, through the Spirit, calls the Messiah "Lord," which means the Christ cannot be merely David\'s biological descendant but must be his divine superior. DIVINE_COUNCIL: Psalm 110 depicts the Messiah enthroned at God\'s right hand, exercising divine rule—a throne-sharing that transcends any merely human kingship.',
        44: 'THEOLOGICAL: This is the climactic christological question of the chapter. If David calls the Christ "Lord" (κύριον), the Messiah must be more than a human descendant of David. Jesus does not deny Davidic sonship but reveals that it is insufficient to explain the Messiah\'s full identity. He is both David\'s son according to the flesh and David\'s Lord according to his divine nature (Rom 1:3-4).',
        47: 'GREEK: κρίμα (krima, "judgment, verdict") here carries the sense of condemnatory sentence. περισσότερον (perissoteron, "more abundant, greater") indicates that those who exploit their religious position for personal gain face a stricter accounting. THEOLOGICAL: The devouring of widows\' houses likely refers to exploiting vulnerable women through excessive legal fees, mismanagement of estates, or extracting hospitality. This warning transitions directly into the widow\'s offering in Luke 21:1-4, creating a deliberate literary contrast.',
    },
    21: {
        2: 'GREEK: The word "πενιχρά" (penichra) appears only here in the NT (hapax legomenon), meaning "needy" or "poor," distinct from "πτωχή" (ptōchē, destitute) used in v.3. Luke uses both terms to emphasize the depth of her poverty. The "λεπτά" (lepta) were the smallest copper coins in circulation, worth about 1/128 of a denarius.',
        4: 'THEOLOGICAL: The contrast between "περισσεύοντος" (perisseúontos, surplus/abundance) and "ὑστερήματος" (hysterēmatos, deficiency/lack) establishes a principle of sacrificial giving that measures not by amount but by cost to the giver. Christ evaluates the heart behind the offering, not the treasury impact. Her giving of "πάντα τὸν βίον" (all her livelihood) prefigures Christ\'s own total self-offering (Phil 2:7-8).',
        6: 'HISTORICAL: Jesus prophesies the destruction of the Jerusalem temple, fulfilled in AD 70 when Roman forces under Titus razed the temple complex. Josephus confirms the thorough destruction (Jewish War 7.1.1). TYPOLOGY: The phrase "stone upon stone" (λίθος ἐπὶ λίθῳ) echoes prophetic judgment language, recalling the desolation oracles of Micah 3:12 and Jeremiah 26:18.',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: The warning "I am he" (Ἐγώ εἰμι) is significant because this is the divine self-identification formula (cf. Exod 3:14 LXX; John 8:58). False messiahs claiming this title usurp the unique authority of Christ. HISTORICAL: Josephus records multiple messianic pretenders before AD 70, including Theudas and the Egyptian (Acts 5:36; 21:38).',
        15: 'GREEK: "Στόμα" (stoma, mouth) here means eloquent speech or utterance — Christ promises not merely words but divinely empowered capacity for speech. The phrase "ᾗ οὐ δυνήσονται ἀντιστῆναι ἢ ἀντειπεῖν" (which they shall not be able to resist or contradict) echoes the promise given to Moses (Exod 4:12) and the wisdom of Stephen (Acts 6:10).',
        22: 'TYPOLOGY: "Days of vengeance" (ἡμέραι ἐκδικήσεως) directly echoes Hosea 9:7 LXX and Isaiah 63:4, linking the destruction of Jerusalem to the covenant-curse pattern of Deuteronomy 28-32. The phrase "to fulfill all the things written" (τοῦ πλησθῆναι πάντα τὰ γεγραμμένα) presents AD 70 as the culmination of prophetic warnings given throughout Israel\'s history (Dan 9:26-27; Lev 26:31-33).',
        24: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Times of the nations" (καιροὶ ἐθνῶν) is a unique Lukan phrase indicating a divinely appointed era during which Gentile dominion over Jerusalem persists. This reflects the prophetic pattern of Daniel\'s successive kingdoms (Dan 2:36-45) and implies an appointed terminus. TYPOLOGY: Jerusalem trampled by nations echoes Daniel 8:13 and Zechariah 12:3, with eschatological restoration implied (Rom 11:25-26).',
        27: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The Son of Man coming in a cloud with power and great glory" directly cites Daniel 7:13-14 LXX, where the one like a Son of Man approaches the Ancient of Days and receives dominion over all nations. DIVINE_COUNCIL: In Daniel 7, this enthronement occurs in the heavenly court amid the divine assembly; the Son of Man receives the kingdom that the hostile spiritual powers ("beasts") attempted to usurp. Christ applies this to himself as the fulfillment of Daniel\'s vision.',
        28: 'GREEK: "Ἀνακύψατε" (anakýpsate) means literally "bend back up" or "stand erect" — a posture of confidence contrasted with the cowering of v.26. "Ἀπολύτρωσις" (apolýtrōsis, redemption/deliverance) carries the sense of ransom-liberation, echoing the Exodus liberation motif. THEOLOGICAL: While the world collapses in terror, believers are to respond with hope because the very events that bring judgment also bring their final deliverance.',
        32: 'THEOLOGICAL: "This generation" (ἡ γενεὰ αὕτη) has been interpreted as (1) the generation alive at Jesus\' speaking, fulfilled in AD 70, (2) the Jewish people as a continuing entity, or (3) the generation witnessing the final signs. The term "γενεά" can mean generation, age, or race. The most contextually grounded reading ties at least the near-fulfillment to the destruction of Jerusalem within approximately forty years.',
        33: 'THEOLOGICAL: Christ claims absolute authority over his own words, placing them above the permanence of the created order. "Heaven and earth shall pass away" echoes Isaiah 51:6 and Psalm 102:25-26, yet Christ\'s words surpass even these. This is an implicit divine claim — only the Word of God endures forever (Isa 40:8; 1 Pet 1:25).',
        36: 'GREEK: "Ἀγρυπνεῖτε" (agrypneîte) means "be sleeplessly watchful," conveying spiritual alertness. "Κατισχύσητε" (katischýsēte) means "to prevail, to have strength sufficient" — implying that escaping these things requires divinely empowered endurance, not mere human effort. THEOLOGICAL: Standing before the Son of Man at his coming is the ultimate goal of faithful discipleship, connecting watchfulness to eschatological vindication (cf. 1 Thess 3:13; Jude 24).',
    },
    22: {
        1: 'HISTORICAL: The Feast of Unleavened Bread (τῶν ἀζύμων) lasted seven days and was closely associated with Passover (πάσχα), such that the terms became interchangeable in common usage. Luke identifies Passover as the name by which this feast was commonly known (ἡ λεγομένη Πάσχα). This sets the theological stage for Jesus as the true Passover lamb (1 Cor 5:7).',
        3: 'THEOLOGICAL: The statement that Satan "entered into" (εἰσῆλθεν εἰς) Judas reflects the biblical concept of malevolent spiritual beings acting upon and through human agents. This is one of only two places in the Gospels where Satan is said to enter a person (cf. John 13:27). DIVINE_COUNCIL: Satan here acts as an adversarial member of the heavenly council (cf. Job 1:6-12; Zech 3:1), operating within divinely permitted boundaries to accomplish what was "determined" (v. 22).',
        7: 'GREEK: The verb θύεσθαι (thyesthai, from θύω, Strong\'s G2380) means "to sacrifice" or "to slaughter," indicating the Passover was understood as a sacrificial offering, not merely a meal. TYPOLOGY: The Passover lamb slain on the 14th of Nisan typologically prefigures Christ, the Lamb of God, whose sacrifice coincides with this very feast (John 1:29; 1 Cor 5:7).',
        15: 'GREEK: The phrase Ἐπιθυμίᾳ ἐπεθύμησα is a Hebraic cognate dative construction (infinitive absolute equivalent), literally "with desire I have desired," expressing the utmost intensity of longing. This Semitic idiom in Luke\'s Greek underscores the gravity of the moment. THEOLOGICAL: Jesus frames this Passover as the climactic fulfillment toward which all prior Passovers pointed.',
        19: 'THEOLOGICAL: The words τοῦτό ἐστιν τὸ σῶμά μου ("this is my body") institute the new covenant meal, connecting the broken bread to Christ\'s sacrificial death. The phrase τὸ ὑπὲρ ὑμῶν διδόμενον ("which is given on behalf of you") uses the present participle, indicating ongoing self-giving. TYPOLOGY: As the Passover lamb\'s body was consumed for Israel\'s deliverance from Egypt, so Christ\'s body is given for the deliverance of God\'s people from sin and death (Exod 12:3-13).',
        20: 'THEOLOGICAL: The "new covenant" (ἡ καινὴ διαθήκη) directly fulfills Jeremiah 31:31-34, where God promised a new covenant to replace the Sinai covenant. The phrase "in my blood" (ἐν τῷ αἵματί μου) parallels Moses\' covenant ratification with blood at Sinai (Exod 24:8). GREEK: διαθήκη (diathēkē, Strong\'s G1242) can mean both "covenant" and "testament/will," carrying the dual sense of a binding agreement ratified by death.',
        22: 'GREEK: The phrase κατὰ τὸ ὡρισμένον ("according to what has been determined") uses ὁρίζω (horizō, Strong\'s G3724), meaning "to mark out boundaries, to determine, to decree." THEOLOGICAL: This affirms divine sovereignty over the crucifixion while simultaneously holding the human betrayer morally responsible — a profound statement of compatibilist theology. God\'s decree does not mitigate Judas\'s culpability.',
        29: 'GREEK: The verb διατίθεμαι (diatíthemai, Strong\'s G1303) means "to covenant, to assign by covenant, to bequeath." Jesus uses the same word twice — "I covenant to you, just as my Father covenanted to me" — establishing a chain of covenantal authority from the Father through the Son to the apostles. THEOLOGICAL: This is a royal grant covenant, in which a king bestows kingdom privileges upon faithful vassals (cf. 2 Sam 7:12-16; Dan 7:14, 27).',
        31: 'GREEK: The verb ἐξῃτήσατο (exēitēsato, from ἐξαιτέω, Strong\'s G1809) is a NT hapax legomenon meaning "to demand for oneself, to obtain by asking." It implies Satan petitioned a higher authority (God) for permission to test the disciples. DIVINE_COUNCIL: This directly parallels Job 1:6-12 and Zechariah 3:1-2, where Satan operates within the divine council framework, requiring permission before acting against God\'s servants. Note that "you" (ὑμᾶς) is plural — Satan sought all the disciples, not Peter alone.',
        32: 'GREEK: ἐδεήθην (edeēthēn, from δέομαι, Strong\'s G1189) indicates earnest supplication; Jesus interceded specifically for Peter (περὶ σοῦ, singular) out of the group Satan demanded. The verb ἐπιστρέψας ("having turned back") presupposes Peter\'s fall before his restoration. THEOLOGICAL: Christ\'s priestly intercession sustains the faith of his own even through failure, anticipating his ongoing high-priestly ministry (Heb 7:25; Rom 8:34).',
        37: 'TYPOLOGY: Jesus quotes Isaiah 53:12 (LXX: μετὰ ἀνόμων ἐλογίσθη, "he was numbered with the lawless"), identifying himself as the Suffering Servant of Isaiah. The phrase τὸ περὶ ἐμοῦ τέλος ἔχει ("that which concerns me has its fulfillment/end") indicates that the Isaianic prophecy reaches its ultimate completion in his imminent passion. THEOLOGICAL: Jesus consciously frames his arrest and death as scriptural fulfillment, not tragic accident.',
        42: 'GREEK: παρένεγκε (parenenke, from παραφέρω, Strong\'s G3911) means "to carry away, to remove." The "cup" (ποτήριον) is a well-established OT metaphor for divine wrath and judgment (Ps 75:8; Isa 51:17, 22; Jer 25:15). THEOLOGICAL: Jesus\' prayer reveals genuine human will ("my will") submitted to the Father\'s will — not a conflict of divine persons, but the incarnate Son\'s human nature shrinking from bearing the cup of wrath while freely yielding to the Father\'s purpose.',
        43: 'HISTORICAL: Verses 43-44 are textually disputed; they are absent from some early manuscripts (P75, א*, A, B) but present in others (א², D, L, and most manuscripts). Most scholars regard them as authentic Lukan material. DIVINE_COUNCIL: An angel (ἄγγελος) from heaven ministers to the incarnate Son — a remarkable scene where a member of God\'s heavenly host strengthens the Lord of that very host, underscoring the reality of Christ\'s full humanity in his suffering.',
        44: 'GREEK: ἀγωνίᾳ (agōnia, Strong\'s G74) denotes intense struggle or anguish, related to the athletic term for a contest (ἀγών). The phrase ὡσεὶ θρόμβοι αἵματος ("like great drops of blood") uses θρόμβοι (thromboi), another NT hapax legomenon, meaning "thick drops" or "clots." Whether this describes actual hematidrosis (a rare medical condition) or is simile for the density and abundance of his sweat, it conveys the extreme intensity of Christ\'s spiritual agony.',
        53: 'THEOLOGICAL: The phrase ἡ ἐξουσία τοῦ σκότους ("the authority of darkness") is theologically profound. Jesus acknowledges a permitted window of satanic and human authority operating against him. DIVINE_COUNCIL: "Darkness" (σκότος) represents the domain and power of hostile spiritual forces (Eph 6:12; Col 1:13). Yet even this "authority" is bounded — it is "your hour," a limited time granted within God\'s sovereign decree (cf. v. 22).',
        61: 'GREEK: The verb ἐνέβλεψεν (eneblepsen, from ἐμβλέπω, Strong\'s G1689) means "to look directly at, to gaze intently into." Luke alone records this piercing look from the Lord to Peter across the courtyard. THEOLOGICAL: This gaze embodies both judgment and mercy — it is the look that breaks Peter and begins his restoration, fulfilling Jesus\' earlier words about Peter\'s turning back (v. 32).',
        69: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus\' declaration that "from now on the Son of Man shall be seated at the right hand of the power of God" combines Daniel 7:13-14 (the Son of Man receiving dominion) with Psalm 110:1 (sitting at God\'s right hand). This is a claim to divine enthronement and co-regency with the Most High — the very claim that provokes the question in v. 70. TYPOLOGY: The "right hand of the power of God" (ἐκ δεξιῶν τῆς δυνάμεως τοῦ θεοῦ) uses "power" (δύναμις) as a reverential circumlocution for God himself, common in Second Temple Judaism.',
        70: 'THEOLOGICAL: The question "You then are the Son of God?" (Σὺ οὖν εἶ ὁ υἱὸς τοῦ θεοῦ;) shows the Sanhedrin understood Jesus\' claim in v. 69 as a claim to divine identity, not merely messiahship. Jesus\' response Ὑμεῖς λέγετε ὅτι ἐγώ εἰμι ("You say that I am") is an affirmative declaration cast in a form that places responsibility on his questioners. The ἐγώ εἰμι ("I am") may also echo the divine self-identification of Exodus 3:14 (LXX). DIVINE_COUNCIL: "Son of God" in its fullest sense designates Jesus not merely as a member of the divine council but as the unique Son who shares the Father\'s nature and throne (cf. Ps 2:7; Heb 1:3-5).',
    },
    23: {
        2: 'GREEK: κατηγορεῖν (katēgorein, Strong\'s G2723) means "to accuse formally in a legal setting." The three charges—perverting the nation, forbidding tribute to Caesar, and claiming to be Christ a king—are crafted to present Jesus as a political threat to Rome. THEOLOGICAL: The charge that he calls himself "Christon Basilea" (Christ, a king) is ironically the most truthful statement his accusers make; Jesus is indeed the Anointed King (Ps 2:2, Dan 7:13-14).',
        3: 'GREEK: "Σὺ λέγεις" (Sy legeis)—"You say it"—is an affirmation that places the declaration back upon Pilate. This is neither evasion nor denial but an indirect confirmation that shifts the weight of the claim onto the questioner. TYPOLOGY: The true King stands before an earthly judge, echoing the reversal pattern of Psalm 2:1-4 where the rulers of the earth set themselves against the Lord and his Anointed.',
        7: 'HISTORICAL: Herod Antipas, tetrarch of Galilee and Perea (4 BC–AD 39), was in Jerusalem for Passover. The term ἐξουσία (exousia) here denotes "jurisdiction" or "domain of authority." Pilate\'s transfer of Jesus to Herod reflects Roman deference to local jurisdictional boundaries. THEOLOGICAL: Two earthly rulers pass judgment on the Lord of glory, fulfilling the pattern of Psalm 2:2: "The kings of the earth set themselves... against the Lord and against his Anointed."',
        12: 'TYPOLOGY: The reconciliation of Herod and Pilate over the condemnation of the innocent Christ echoes Psalm 2:1-2—the nations rage, and rulers conspire together against the Lord\'s Anointed (cf. Acts 4:25-28, where the early church explicitly cites this passage with reference to Herod and Pilate). THEOLOGICAL: The enmity of the world finds unity only in opposition to the Christ.',
        25: 'THEOLOGICAL: The substitutionary exchange is stark: a man guilty of insurrection (στάσις) and murder (φόνος) is released, while the innocent one is delivered (παρέδωκεν, paradidōmi—the same word used for Judas\'s betrayal) to the will of the mob. TYPOLOGY: This exchange prefigures the atonement itself—the guilty go free while the righteous one bears their condemnation (Isa 53:5-6; 2 Cor 5:21).',
        30: 'TYPOLOGY: Jesus quotes Hosea 10:8, a prophetic oracle against the idolatrous Northern Kingdom. The language of mountains falling and hills covering is apocalyptic judgment imagery, applied here to the coming destruction of Jerusalem in AD 70. This passage is also echoed in Revelation 6:16, where the same cry is directed at the Lamb in the final judgment.',
        31: 'GREEK: ξύλῳ ὑγρῷ (xylō hygrō, "green wood") versus ξηρῷ (xērō, "dry")—a proverbial saying. The "green wood" represents the living, innocent Jesus; the "dry wood" represents the guilty nation ripe for judgment. THEOLOGICAL: If Rome does this to the innocent one, what will befall the guilty? This is a prophetic warning of the destruction of Jerusalem (AD 70).',
        34: 'THEOLOGICAL: The prayer "Father, forgive them, for they do not know what they are doing" is textually disputed (absent in some early manuscripts including P75 and Codex Vaticanus) but attested in Sinaiticus and the majority of witnesses. It displays the intercessory role of the Messiah even on the cross (cf. Isa 53:12, "he bore the sin of many and made intercession for the transgressors"). TYPOLOGY: The casting of lots for his garments fulfills Psalm 22:18 (LXX 21:19): "They divided my garments among them, and for my clothing they cast lots."',
        35: 'GREEK: ἐξεμυκτήριζον (exemyktērizon, Strong\'s G1592)—literally "to turn up the nose at," a vivid term for derision found only in Luke in the NT. TYPOLOGY: The taunt "He saved others; let him save himself" unwittingly echoes Psalm 22:7-8 (LXX 21:8-9): "He trusted in God; let him deliver him." The title "the Christ of God, the Chosen One" (ho Christos tou theou ho eklektos) links to Isaiah 42:1, the Chosen Servant of the Lord.',
        43: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus\'s declaration "Today you shall be with me in Paradise" (παραδείσῳ, paradeisō, Strong\'s G3857, a Persian loanword used in the LXX for the Garden of Eden in Gen 2:8) affirms the immediate conscious presence of the redeemed with Christ after death. GREEK: παράδεισος in Second Temple Jewish literature referred to the blessed abode of the righteous dead (cf. 2 Cor 12:4; Rev 2:7). This is the only use of the word in the Gospels.',
        45: 'THEOLOGICAL: The tearing of the temple veil (καταπέτασμα τοῦ ναοῦ, katapetasma tou naou) signifies the opening of access to the divine presence. The inner veil separated the Holy Place from the Most Holy Place (Exod 26:33). Its rending from top indicates divine action. TYPOLOGY: Hebrews 10:19-20 interprets this veil as Christ\'s flesh—through his death a new and living way is opened into the true Holy of Holies. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The barrier between the divine throne room and humanity is removed by the sacrifice of the incarnate Son.',
        46: 'GREEK: παρατίθεμαι (paratithēmi, Strong\'s G3908)—"I commit, I entrust, I deposit." Jesus quotes Psalm 31:5 (LXX 30:6), a psalm of trust in the Lord. THEOLOGICAL: Unlike Mark\'s account of the cry of dereliction (Mark 15:34, quoting Ps 22:1), Luke records Jesus dying with a prayer of trust and self-surrender to the Father, demonstrating his unbroken communion with God even in death. The voluntary nature of his death is emphasized: he commits his spirit; it is not taken from him (cf. John 10:18).',
        47: 'GREEK: δίκαιος (dikaios)—"righteous, just, innocent." The centurion\'s declaration in Luke is "righteous" rather than "Son of God" as in Mark/Matthew. THEOLOGICAL: A Gentile Roman soldier recognizes the righteousness of the one condemned by both Jewish leaders and Roman authority, previewing the Gentile mission. This echoes the Suffering Servant of Isaiah 53:11: "the righteous one, my servant, shall make many to be accounted righteous."',
        51: 'GREEK: προσεδέχετο (prosedecheto, Strong\'s G4327)—imperfect tense, "was waiting for, was expectantly receiving." THEOLOGICAL: Joseph of Arimathea embodies the faithful remnant of Israel who awaited the kingdom of God (cf. Luke 2:25, 38 where Simeon and Anna likewise awaited redemption). His dissent from the Sanhedrin\'s decision shows that not all of Israel\'s council rejected their Messiah.',
        53: 'TYPOLOGY: The detail that the tomb was hewn in stone and that no one had yet been laid in it (cf. John 19:41) parallels the prophetic significance of purity and newness—the body of the Holy One would see no corruption (Ps 16:10; Acts 2:27). HISTORICAL: Rock-hewn tombs (λαξευτός, laxeutos, a NT hapax legomenon) were costly and typically belonged to wealthy families, fulfilling Isaiah 53:9: "with a rich man in his death."',
        54: 'GREEK: παρασκευή (paraskeuē, Strong\'s G3904)—the technical term for Friday, the day of Preparation before the Sabbath. ἐπέφωσκεν (epephōsken)—"was dawning," but Jewish days begin at sunset, so this likely means the Sabbath lights were beginning to appear at dusk. HISTORICAL: The urgency to complete the burial before the Sabbath began at sundown shaped the haste of the burial proceedings.',
        56: 'THEOLOGICAL: The women\'s preparation of spices and ointments, followed by Sabbath rest "according to the commandment" (κατὰ τὴν ἐντολήν), demonstrates their Torah-faithfulness even in grief. TYPOLOGY: The Sabbath rest between crucifixion and resurrection carries deep typological weight—the Creator rested on the seventh day (Gen 2:2-3), and now the Redeemer rests in the tomb on the Sabbath before the new creation dawns on the first day of the week.',
    },
    24: {
        1: 'GREEK: "τῇ μιᾷ τῶν σαββάτων" (tē mia tōn sabbatōn) literally "on the first of the sabbaths," a Semitic idiom for the first day of the week (Sunday). HISTORICAL: Jewish custom required waiting until after the Sabbath rest to prepare a body with spices; the women\'s early arrival underscores their devotion and urgency.',
        4: 'GREEK: "ἐσθῆτι ἀστραπτούσῃ" (esthēti astraptousē) — "lightning-flashing garments." The participle ἀστράπτω (Strong\'s G797) denotes the brilliance of lightning. DIVINE_COUNCIL: Angelic beings appearing in radiant garments is consistent with divine council messenger imagery (cf. Dan 10:5-6; Acts 1:10). Two witnesses establish testimony under Torah law (Deut 19:15).',
        5: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Why do you seek the living among the dead?" — This rhetorical question from the angels contains a profound christological declaration: Jesus belongs to the category of "the living" (τὸν ζῶντα), not "the dead" (τῶν νεκρῶν). This echoes divine self-identification language (cf. Josh 3:10; Ps 42:2; Dan 6:26).',
        7: 'THEOLOGICAL: The phrase "δεῖ παραδοθῆναι" (dei paradothēnai, "it is necessary to be delivered") expresses divine necessity—the cross was not accidental but ordained in the counsel of God. TYPOLOGY: The three-fold pattern—delivered, crucified, risen on the third day—becomes the kerygmatic core of apostolic preaching (cf. 1 Cor 15:3-4).',
        11: 'GREEK: "λῆρος" (lēros, Strong\'s G3026) is a NT hapax legomenon meaning "idle talk, nonsense, delirium." It was used in medical literature for the babbling of the fevered. The disciples\' disbelief of the women\'s testimony heightens the apologetic force of the resurrection narrative—they were not credulous.',
        16: 'GREEK: "ἐκρατοῦντο" (ekratounto) is a divine passive—their eyes "were being held" (by God). THEOLOGICAL: The supernatural restraint on recognition indicates that the risen Christ\'s identity is disclosed by divine initiative, not by human perception alone. This parallels the theme of spiritual blindness and divine revelation throughout Luke-Acts.',
        21: 'GREEK: "λυτροῦσθαι τὸν Ἰσραήλ" (lytrousthai ton Israēl, "to redeem Israel") uses the middle voice of λυτρόω (Strong\'s G3084), reflecting OT redemption language (cf. Ps 130:8 LXX; Isa 41:14). THEOLOGICAL: Their hope was not wrong in substance—Jesus is indeed the Redeemer—but was incomplete in understanding the mode: redemption through suffering before glory.',
        25: 'GREEK: "ἀνόητοι" (anoētoi, "without understanding/foolish") and "βραδεῖς τῇ καρδίᾳ" (bradeis tē kardia, "slow in heart") — the heart in Hebraic thought is the seat of understanding, not merely emotion. THEOLOGICAL: Jesus rebukes not intellectual incapacity but a failure of the heart to trust the prophetic witness. Faith must encompass the whole prophetic testimony, including the suffering of the Messiah.',
        26: 'THEOLOGICAL: "οὐχὶ ταῦτα ἔδει παθεῖν τὸν χριστόν" — "Was it not necessary for the Christ to suffer?" The divine "δεῖ" (dei, divine necessity) governs both the suffering (παθεῖν) and the entrance into glory (εἰσελθεῖν εἰς τὴν δόξαν). TYPOLOGY: This establishes the suffering-then-glory pattern as the definitive hermeneutical key for reading the OT messianic witness (cf. 1 Pet 1:10-11; Isa 53; Ps 22).',
        27: 'GREEK: "διερμήνευσεν" (diermēneusen, Strong\'s G1329) means "to interpret thoroughly, to translate/expound." THEOLOGICAL: This is the paradigmatic christological reading of Scripture: beginning from Moses (Torah) through all the prophets, Jesus demonstrates that the entire OT testifies concerning himself. This verse is foundational for Christian hermeneutics—Christ is the interpretive center of all Scripture.',
        31: 'GREEK: "ἄφαντος" (aphantos, Strong\'s G855) is a NT hapax legomenon meaning "invisible, vanished from sight." THEOLOGICAL: Recognition comes precisely at the breaking of bread (τῇ κλάσει τοῦ ἄρτου), echoing the Last Supper (Luke 22:19). The risen Christ is known not merely by sight but through the sacramental act he instituted. His vanishing underscores that his post-resurrection presence operates in a new mode.',
        34: 'GREEK: "ὄντως ἠγέρθη ὁ κύριος" — "Truly the Lord has been raised." The adverb ὄντως (ontōs, "in reality, truly") emphasizes the factual nature of the resurrection. THEOLOGICAL: The title "ὁ κύριος" (ho kyrios, "the Lord") applied to the risen Jesus carries its fullest theological weight here, identifying the risen Christ with the divine Lord of Israel (cf. Ps 110:1; Phil 2:11).',
        39: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus\' emphatic "ἐγώ εἰμι αὐτός" (egō eimi autos, "I am he myself") combined with the invitation to touch his flesh and bones establishes bodily resurrection against any docetic or purely spiritual interpretation. The resurrection body is continuous with the crucified body—bearing the marks of the nails—yet transformed beyond ordinary physicality.',
        44: 'THEOLOGICAL: Jesus identifies three divisions of the Hebrew Scriptures—the Law of Moses, the Prophets, and the Psalms (representing the Writings/Ketuvim)—as testifying about himself. This is the only NT text explicitly naming all three divisions of the Tanakh. STRUCTURE: This verse forms the theological climax of the Emmaus narrative expanded: all Scripture finds its fulfillment ("δεῖ πληρωθῆναι," must be fulfilled) in the person and work of Christ.',
        45: 'GREEK: "διήνοιξεν αὐτῶν τὸν νοῦν" — "he opened their mind." The verb διανοίγω (dianoigō, Strong\'s G1272) is the same used for opening the womb (Luke 2:23), opening eyes (v.31), and opening Scriptures (v.32). THEOLOGICAL: Understanding Scripture requires divine illumination; the noetic effect of sin prevents natural comprehension of the christological content of the OT. Only the risen Lord can grant this spiritual sight.',
        47: 'GREEK: "μετάνοιαν καὶ ἄφεσιν ἁμαρτιῶν" (metanoian kai aphesin hamartiōn) — "repentance and forgiveness of sins." THEOLOGICAL: The content of the proclamation flows directly from the suffering and resurrection of the Christ (v.46). "Εἰς πάντα τὰ ἔθνη" (eis panta ta ethnē, "to all the nations") fulfills the Abrahamic promise (Gen 12:3) and Isaianic vision (Isa 49:6). The phrase "ἀρξάμενοι ἀπὸ Ἰερουσαλήμ" ("beginning from Jerusalem") establishes the geographic-theological program fulfilled in Acts.',
        49: 'THEOLOGICAL: "τὴν ἐπαγγελίαν τοῦ πατρός μου" — "the promise of my Father." Jesus identifies the coming Holy Spirit as the Father\'s promise, linking to Joel 2:28-32 and the Pentecost fulfillment in Acts 2. "Δύναμιν ἐξ ὕψους" (dynamin ex hypsous, "power from on high") — ὕψος connotes the heavenly realm, the divine throne (cf. Isa 32:15; Luke 1:35). STRUCTURE: This verse bridges Luke\'s Gospel to Acts, creating a literary and theological hinge for the two-volume work.',
        51: 'THEOLOGICAL: "ἀνεφέρετο εἰς τὸν οὐρανόν" — "he was carried up into heaven." The imperfect passive ἀνεφέρετο depicts an ongoing, visible ascension. TYPOLOGY: The ascension fulfills the enthronement pattern of Psalm 110:1 and Daniel 7:13-14, where the Son of Man approaches the Ancient of Days and receives dominion. Jesus\' departure while blessing (εὐλογεῖν) echoes the high-priestly blessing (Num 6:22-27; Sir 50:20-21), casting him as the true and final High Priest.',
        52: 'GREEK: "προσκυνήσαντες αὐτόν" (proskynēsantes auton) — "having worshiped him." The verb προσκυνέω (proskyneō, Strong\'s G4352) denotes full religious worship, the homage due to God alone. THEOLOGICAL: The disciples\' worship of the ascended Jesus constitutes a profound christological confession—they recognize in the risen and ascended Christ one worthy of the worship belonging to the God of Israel. Their "great joy" contrasts with the sorrow of the passion and confirms the resurrection\'s transformative power.',
        53: 'STRUCTURE: Luke\'s Gospel ends where it began—in the temple (cf. Luke 1:8-10). The inclusion forms a literary frame: from Zechariah\'s priestly service to the disciples\' continuous worship. THEOLOGICAL: "εὐλογοῦντες τὸν θεόν" — "blessing God." The proper response to the resurrection, ascension, and promised Spirit is unceasing doxology. The open ending anticipates Acts, where the Spirit descends and the mission to all nations begins.',
    },
}